<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 09:22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Romney Hopes To Save Utah Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- In another six months, Mitt Romney hopes  
to have ``all the lines connected and the boxes filled'' in his 
quest to rebuild the Salt Lake Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the third president of the local Olympic organization --  
and the one with perhaps the toughest job -- is seeking sponsors and 
budget cuts, and learning how to say no. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to say I'm looking for heroes of all stripes to save  
our bacon, to help us find ways to reduce costs and to also support 
the games,'' Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past week, Romney has spent many hours with someone who  
knows what he's going through -- Jean-Claude Killy, the triple 
gold-medal skier and co-president of the 1992 Albertville Games who 
is now an IOC member from France. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been an eye-opening experience for Romney, the venture  
capitalist from Boston who returned three months ago to the state 
where he spent his youth. He arrived in the middle of the Olympic 
bribery scandal to try to solve problems he inherited. 
</P>
<P>
	Killy is vice-chairman of the International Olympic Committee  
task force coordinating preparations for the 2002 Winter Games, and 
Romney said his presence during a week of meetings was ``very 
powerful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He has been where I am now and he continues to give very, very  
good advice to me,'' Romney said. ``He told me how many people are 
going to come asking for more. He said. `Mitt, you have to learn 
just to say no, I'm sorry, we can't do that.' 
</P>
<P>
	``And he said, `It's tough, you're telling everyone no and  
you'll be criticized by many, many people and the public and the 
media. But when the games begin, people will appreciate what's been 
built.''' 
</P>
<P>
	What Romney wants to build is a lasting monument to Olympic  
athletes and sports, while paying the bills and making sure 
everything is neat and tidy when the games end on Feb. 24, 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``People here are anxious to get on with the games and sport,  
and to stop dwelling on the administration and the failures of 
management,'' he said. ``The energy here is in regards to new 
sponsors, mascots, sport, going forward. And I had not expected it 
would be so immediate. The support has been very heartening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romney is the son of one of the most celebrated couples in  
American public service, former Michigan Gov. George Romney and his 
wife, Lenora. 
</P>
<P>
	A failed challenger for Ted Kennedy's Senate seat from  
Massachusetts in 1994, Romney made his mark by reviving troubled 
companies as CEO of Bain Capital Inc. Domino's pizza and Staples 
office supplies are two of his success stories. 
</P>
<P>
	He was recruited to head the Salt Lake Organizing Committee when  
Frank Joklik, the retired chairman of Kennecott copper, resigned in 
the midst of the million-dollar scandal over improper inducements 
to IOC members from Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	And in his three months on the job, the 52-year-old graduate of  
BYU and Harvard Business School has attacked SLOC's problems as he 
would those of any foundering organization -- cutting costs, looking 
for new income and changing its image. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, he said, $98 million has been trimmed from SLOC's budget  
and more paring is planned. 
</P>
<P>
	And earlier this month, Romney announced deals totaling some $30  
million with three new sponsors -- the first major signings since 
the scandal broke last November, but far from the $300 million in 
sponsorships SLOC needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney and the IOC spent much of the week talking money, and the  
SLOC president said he hoped for breakthroughs soon in the ``virgin 
territory'' of sponsorships from information-technology companies, 
a growing Utah resource. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of those technology companies have not been called on,  
ever, to consider a sponsorship of the Olympics and Olympic 
teams,'' he said. ``And think of those Internet companies -- they 
weren't even here! I don't know if E-Bay existed at the time of 
Atlanta'' which played host to the games in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Such high-tech sponsors also would open the door to Romney's  
view of worldwide Olympic marketing right in your home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have pins and memorabilia and licensed products  
and maybe even tickets that get sold on the Internet,'' he said. 
``And we haven't even worked with companies like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other sponsor slots Romney wants to fill include an  
international automaker, chemical and pharmaceutical firms and 
various food products, including cereals. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also considering an approach to federal agencies to use the  
Winter Games as a platform for various programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may be able to be a demonstration project for a drug-free  
America, or a demonstration project for the Energy Department or 
the EPA,'' he said. ``We have a number of things that from my point 
of view are important from a precedent standpoint and communicate 
what can be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC's image has been buffed by Romney's direct but casual  
style. He acted like a talk-show host and looked like the emcee of 
a country-music concert when he helped introduce the games' new 
mascots -- a snowshoe hare, a coyote and a black bear -- to a 
cheering audience last weekend. He invited the IOC members to his 
house for dinner, the only social function on their calendar. He 
strolls SLOC's offices with his smile on and his suit jacket off. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposed budget cuts have not always produced smiles. The  
U.S. Olympic Committee is negotiating to save $5 million in 
operating cuts for pre-games training at ski jumps, bobsled and 
luge tracks and the speedskating oval, eliminating free practice 
time it says Romney's predecessors promised. 
</P>
<P>
	The new SLOC boss says his proposal ``doesn't strike me as being  
an outrageous request,'' since SLOC spent $170 million to build the 
facilities and will still pay two-thirds of the operating costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney even has gone after perhaps the most sacred cow of  
Olympic finance -- the money spent on IOC members during the games. 
He's asked the committee to pick up a bigger share of the 
multimillion-dollar tab, including hotel charges. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, he hasn't been told no.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's been refreshing -- they haven't come here saying `We want  
more of this' or `Give us more,''' he said. ``Instead it's been, 
`How can we be helpful to the games?''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
