<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Catinca Captures Shuvee Handicap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Catinca was up in the final strides today to  
capture the Grade II $150,000 Shuvee Handicap for fillies and mares 
3-years-old and up at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in three years that trainer John Kimmel  
and jockey Richard Migliore had teamed up to capture the Shuvee 
Handicap. Two years ago, it was Hidden Lake who got the job done. 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's 24th running of the race, Catinca captured the  
$90,000 winner's share for Robert K. Waxman. 
</P>
<P>
	It also was the third time in the Shuvee's last 10 runnings that  
Migliore rode the winner. In 1990, he was aboard for Tis Juliet's 
winning trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Sister Act, who contended for the lead throughout, lasted to be  
runnerup in the six horse field, 1 1/2 lengths before Tap to Music. 
</P>
<P>
	The win was the second in four starts this year for Catinca and  
the second straight for added money. The 4-year-old daughter of 
Storm Cat from the Saratoga Six mare, Inca Legacy, reported home 
first in Aqueduct's Grade III Bed o'Roses Handicap in her previous 
start on April 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Catinca carried highweight of 121 and Migliore one mile in 1:34  
1-5 on the fast track and returned $7.50, $3.10 and $2.40. Sister 
Act paid $3.10 and $2.30, and Tap to Music was $2.70. 
</P>
</TEXT>
