<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Works Social Security Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTERSET, Iowa -- (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House  
Budget Committee and a presidential hopeful, said Saturday he's 
working on a plan to shore up Social Security that may call for 
``some sacrifice'' from baby boomers. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in Iowa, Kasich said his proposal would allow  
private investment of at least some of the money now collected in 
Social Security taxes. But given the number of people nearing an 
age to withdraw retirement pensions, private investment might not 
be enough to keep the system afloat, Kasich said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There may be some sacrifice involved,'' he said. ``The  
question is, when do we phase this program in. It may be that the 
baby boomers take a hit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa, where February precinct caucuses make the nation's first  
candidate selections for the 2000 campaign, has the third oldest 
population in the nation. Kasich, R-Ohio, said he rejects such 
traditional Social Security cuts as raising the retirement age or 
limiting cost-of-living increases. 
</P>
<P>
	He would not offer details about his plan but said it is clear  
that some groups will have to sacrifice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still running the numbers,'' Kasich said. ``I'm  
developing a plan. It may be that sacrifice is needed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move carries great political significance for Kasich. In  
addition to his Budget Committee post, he is exploring the 
possibility of a bid for the Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich said his plan calls for taking a portion of the Social  
Security tax and returning it to taxpayers who, in turn, would 
invest in a preselected menu of investment options. 
</P>
<P>
	Most economic projections assume a monthly 5 percent investment  
return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
