<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Areas Gird for New Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Eight months after Hurricane Georges sent  
a neighbor's fishing boat crashing through his living room wall, 
John Strock is still sleeping in his garage. 
</P>
<P>
	The waterfront cottage his father built hasn't been repaired  
since the storm rumbled through on Sept. 25, and Strock's 
neighborhood in Big Pine Key, just off the Florida Keys' Overseas 
Highway, still looks like a garbage dump. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything was just basically destroyed,'' said Strock, 64.  
``The water heater was found down the street. They say we're at the 
top of the list for repairs, but it's starting to get hot and the 
new season is approaching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another six-month Atlantic hurricane season starts June 1, and  
some areas of the Florida Keys, Honduras, Haiti and the Dominican 
Republic hit by last year's monster storms are unprepared for 
another round that could be equally brutal. 
</P>
<P>
	After one of the deadliest seasons on record, hurricane  
forecasters say cyclical changes such as African rainfall and ocean 
temperatures could signal an upswing of storm activity not seen for 
50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	And La Nina, the weather phenomenon believed to contribute to an  
increase in hurricanes that make landfall, will continue well into 
the season. La Nina turns the Pacific Ocean waters colder and plays 
the same weather tricks in reverse -- rain where it was dry and vice 
versa. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have been saying for several years we may be heading  
back to a period like the '40s and '50s when we really had heavy 
hurricane seasons -- a lot of major hurricanes,'' said Jerry 
Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center in Miami. ``I 
think it's no longer speculation. I think we are in it now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The period from 1995 to '98 yielded 53 named storms, 33 of them  
gaining hurricane status, 15 rising to the level of a major 
hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	William Gray, the Colorado State University professor noted for  
his accuracy in forecasting hurricane frequency, has never 
predicted a season with more than 11 named storms -- until this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	For 1999, Gray predicts 14 storms strong enough to be named --  
nine hurricanes, four of them major. Gray will update his 
prediction the first week of June. If the forecast is accurate, the 
hope is that the big hurricanes will at least stay over water. 
</P>
<P>
	The opposite happened last season when Georges, a Category 4  
storm with maximum sustained winds near 150 mph, went 
island-hopping through the Caribbean in late September. More than 
500 people lost their lives in Haiti and the Dominican Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	A month later, along came Mitch -- a monstrous Category 5 storm  
that stalled off the coast of Honduras. The toll: at least 10,000 
dead and 2 million homeless in Honduras and Nicaragua. 
</P>
<P>
	``In terms of casualties,'' Jarrell said, ``it looks like now  
it's probably the worst year since 1780'' -- when a hurricane killed 
at least 22,000 people on Martinique, Barbados and surrounding 
islands. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nicaragua, recent spring rains uncovered the bones of those  
buried in mudslides. Many Hondurans have been left to rebuild homes 
on the banks of the same rivers that flooded and unleashed deadly 
mudslides. 
</P>
<P>
	``These people should pay attention to the sounds of the hills  
and mountains,'' said Oscar Triminio of the Honduras fire 
department. ``Only by doing that will they avoid dying covered by 
mud.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Across the Caribbean Sea in the Dominican Republic, officials'  
slow response to Georges may have cost hundreds of lives. In the 
disaster's wake, Chicago Cubs baseball star Sammy Sosa collected 
more aid money than his native country's government. He sent 
planeloads of food and medical supplies to his hometown of San 
Pedro de Macoris. 
</P>
<P>
	In the lower Florida Keys, people are still wrestling with  
insurance companies and trying to replace or repair their homes. 
Relief workers say they can only hope a hurricane doesn't find the 
lower Keys for the second consecutive year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like to say I pray more than I used to, but I'm going  
to really pray through this hurricane season,'' said Suzanne Lex, 
coordinator of Paradise Interfaith Network which formed to help 
Georges' victims rebuild in the Keys. About 125 families are still 
receiving assistance, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Keys remain one of the most vulnerable places for a  
hurricane. Georges had weakened by the time it reached the United 
States, but had it been even slightly stronger there could have 
been deaths, Jarrell said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got really lucky,'' he said. ``If we had a Category 3 or 4  
storm I think we would have lost a whole bunch of people in Key 
West.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of the 77,000 year-round residents of the Keys,  
as well as some tourists, refused to heed the evacuation order. 
Nearly 30,000 people bore out the storm in Key West -- the 
southernmost island in the delicate chain, and a tourist mecca. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrell said people are afraid to leave for fear of being  
stranded when the storm hits on the two-lane, 110-mile Overseas 
Highway, the only highway through the Keys. He worries some people 
won't leave before the next hurricane because they had so much 
trouble returning to their homes on the clogged highway after 
Georges. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless we can get something done about that road we are  
destined sooner or later to kill a bunch of people,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
