<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- The Volcano of Fire just west of the  
capital awoke from a 21-year slumber and erupted with a blast of 
ash and rock, national disaster officials said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen people were evacuated from a farm near the 12,417-foot  
volcano but there were no reports of injury or damage, fireman 
Pedro Cojolon Perez said in a telephone interview from Alotenango, 
a town at the base of the volcano. 
</P>
<P>
	The volcano erupted late Friday but appeared calm Saturday  
morning. It last erupted in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Moving to more closely control breast  
implants, Brazilian legislators have voted to ban injections of 
liquid silicone in humans and restrict the use of silicon implants. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, which was passed the lower house Thursday and now  
goes to the Senate, will make silicone implants available only 
through medical specialists. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked by how many people have been harmed by silicone  
and to what extent. Many of their organs have been irreparably 
damaged, and one woman will soon die because of a cancer caused by 
her silicone implants,'' said Deputy Miro Teixeira, the bill's 
sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	Teixeira said he was prompted to action by a group called  
Victims of Silicone, which works to raise public awareness of 
silicone's dangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Many women blame implants for a variety of ailments.  
Manufacturers deny their products are dangerous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
