<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Nick at Nite' Announces New Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Maude'' is back in the spotlight, and Beatrice  
Arthur thinks she knows why: It's still relevant today, she says, 
21 years after it left the air. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's adult, and it's literate,'' says Arthur, 73. ``And it's  
full of people who question things. Young people like anything that 
questions the old values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur joined stars from top 1970s sitcoms -- Loni Anderson and  
Howard Hesseman of ``WKRP in Cincinnati'' and John Ritter and Don 
Knotts of ``Three's Company'' -- at a luncheon Friday to introduce 
the new lineup for the nostalgia-television programming on 
Nickelodeon's ``Nick at Nite'' and its sister channel, TV Land. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maude'' begins airing in August on TV Land.  
</P>
<P>
	A spinoff of Norman Lear's lauded ``All in the Family,''  
``Maude'' ran from 1972 to 1978 on CBS. starring Arthur as Edith 
Bunker's liberal cousin, Maude Findlay. The show, though a comedy, 
became a vehicle for issues TV had long avoided, such as abortion, 
alcoholism, homosexuality and racial tension. 
</P>
<P>
	``Norman Lear was a pioneer. We had great actors --  
theater-trained actors -- and wonderful directing,'' Arthur says. 
``And Norman took risks. We tackled everything.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
