<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Greater Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	IRVINGTON, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton tonight said that the  
key to reducing youth violence lies in the family and community. 
Speaking at Sons of Italy Foundation's annual dinner, Clinton 
called on parents to lead by example and show the country's 
children the evils of prejudice. He asked the audience to provide 
``every decent person a home in America'' and cited NATO's mission 
against Yugoslavia as an example of living by such values. Earlier 
today, Clinton pressed the House for swift passage of gun-control 
legislation. Senators approved legislation last week that would 
require safety locks on new handguns, ban violent juveniles from 
purchasing a firearm, and stop the import of large ammunition 
clips. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Admits Hitting Albanian Post  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO kept up its attacks on  
Yugoslavia early Sunday. Scores of missiles and bombs were 
reportedly sent at targets across the country. Meanwhile, NATO 
officials acknowledged alliance forces accidentally attacked a 
stronghold of the Kosovo Liberation Army Friday. International 
monitors said at least one KLA guerrilla was killed and at least 15 
others wounded in the strike against the hilltop border post in 
Kosare, 37 miles west of Kosovo's capital, Pristina. 

</P>
<P>
	India Criticizes NATO Mission  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India is protesting damage to its  
ambassador's residence in a NATO attack on Yugoslavia's capital. 
Today India also reiterated its demand that the bombings be called 
off. The foreign office said that Indian property was damaged in a 
strike Thursday when NATO bombers targeted sites close to the 
ambassador's residence. No one was injured in the ambassador's 
house. India, which has opposed the aerial bombings, supports a 
negotiated political solution to the conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Makah Celebrate Whale Hunt Success  
</P>
<P>
	NEAH BAY, Wash. (AP) -- Makah Indians joined with neighboring  
tribes today to celebrate their first successful whale hunt since 
the 1920s. On Monday, a crew from the tribe killed a gray whale 
using a harpoon and a .50 caliber rifle. The kill renewed a 
tradition guaranteed by the tribe's 1855 treaty but abandoned 
decades ago when commercial whaling decimated the species. 
Anti-whaling activists contend such hunting is illegal and fear it 
will lead to a worldwide renewal of commercial whaling. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Computers Found Easy To Hack  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A government investigation into NASA's cyber  
security found it so vulnerable to attack that hackers could easily 
disrupt command and control operations, including the tracking of 
earth-orbiting spacecraft. The General Accounting Office, the 
investigative arm of Congress, said that its teams also penetrated 
systems that process and distribute the National Aeronautics and 
Space Administration's scientific data and broke into many of 
NASA's most vital networks. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-U.S. Official To Visit N. Korea  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea confirmed today an  
upcoming visit by former Defense Secretary William Perry. However, 
authorities did not say whether President Clinton's envoy will meet 
with communist leader Kim Jong Il. Perry will be making the first 
official visit to the isolated communist state by a U.S. official 
representing the president. Kim Jong Il rarely meets with foreign 
officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Museum Strike Closes Louvre, Others  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The ``Mona Lisa'' smiled to an empty room today as  
striking workers kept tourists and art lovers out of many Paris 
museums and monuments for a fourth day. The Louvre remained closed, 
as did the Arc de Triomphe and the Pantheon, the resting place of 
France's greatest minds, union leaders said. Unions representing 
the employees are set to meet Tuesday to decide whether to continue 
their walkout. 

</P>
<P>
	Statue Erected in Memory of Joyner  
</P>
<P>
	LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- The husband and 8-year-old daughter  
of the late Florence Griffith Joyner helped unveil a statue in 
memory of the three-time Olympic gold medalist. ``Seeing it and 
feeling it, I almost think it's her. (But) all I have is her 
spirit,'' Al Joyner, accompanied by daughter Mary, said yesterday. 
The statue depicts the world's fastest female sprinter with hands 
raised in victory as she crossed the finish line in the 100 meters 
at the 1988 Seoul Olympics. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche Beat Stars 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A period after having a possible goal waved off,  
Valeri Kamensky rebounded his own miss with 5:58 left to give 
Colorado a 2-1 victory over Dallas in the opening game of the 
Western Conference finals tonight. The Avalanche improved to 7-0 on 
the road this postseason and won their fifth straight since being 
down 0-2 to Detroit in the second round. The Stars had won their 
first five playoff games in Reunion Arena. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
