<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McKillop To Stay at Davidson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIDSON, N.C. (AP) -- Bob McKillop will remain men's basketball  
coach at Davidson after weighing an offer to take a similar post at 
Stony Brook. 
</P>
<P>
	McKillop said Friday he decided to stay with the Wildcats after  
being pursued by the Long Island school and athletic director 
Richard Laskowski, a longtime friend of McKillop's. 
</P>
<P>
	McKillop, a former New York resident, said he contemplated the  
situation more seriously than any other offer in his 10 seasons at 
Davidson. McKillop, who was a serious candidate for the St. John's 
opening before last season, said the chance to work with Laskowski 
was tempting. 
</P>
<P>
	McKillop did not receive a contract extension or raise at  
Davidson, but was given reassurances by school officials about the 
direction of the program and the school's financial commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are absolutely delighted not only that Bob will continue as  
head coach but that the conversation surrounding this process has 
yielded long-term stability for our basketball program and for Bob 
himself,'' Davidson athletics director Jim Murphy. 
</P>
<P>
	McKillop has compiled a 154-131 record while building one of the  
strongest programs in the Southern Conference. Davidson won the 
league championship and the automatic NCAA berth in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Stony Brook will begin its first season in Division I in  
1999-2000 and does not have a conference affiliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
