<DOCNO> APW19990522.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians, Tigers Get Into Brawl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Manny Ramirez was ejected following a brawl in  
the bottom of the sixth inning Saturday as the Cleveland Indians 
and Detroit Tigers exchanged beanballs, pushes and shoves. 
</P>
<P>
	In the top of the sixth, Cleveland starter Jaret Wright, who was  
suspended earlier this season for a brawl in Boston, hit Tony Clark 
in the helmet one batter after giving up a two-run double to Dean 
Palmer that put the Tigers ahead 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, leading off the bottom of the inning, was then hit in  
the head by Detroit rookie Jeff Weaver. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez shouted at Weaver as he slowly walked toward first base  
before dashing across the diamond after the right-hander. He was 
met on top of the pitching mound by umpire Jim Evans, who put his 
hands out like a traffic cop in an attempt to stop Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	Both benches and bullpens emptied and several small skirmishes  
broke out before order was restored. 
</P>
<P>
	After Ramirez was ejected, plate umpire Chuck Meriwether warned  
both teams about any further retaliation, but that didn't stop 
Wright from coming inside with a pitch to Juan Encarnacion in the 
seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	In the eighth, Tigers reliever C.J. Nitkowski knocked Kenny  
Lofton down with his first -- and only -- pitch and was immediately 
tossed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Students Return to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- Students returning to Heritage High School  
on Saturday to collect books, bags and jackets they left during 
last week's shooting said they encountered an eerily calm campus. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time students were allowed back since Thursday,  
when a sophomore began firing a rifle into a commons area, wounding 
six. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was sort of an eeriness that came over you, knowing that  
there was somebody in your school shooting,'' said Alexis Diamond, 
a 16-year-old sophomore who had gone to retrieve her jacket from a 
science classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile the fifth of the six shooting victims was released  
from the hospital. The only student still hospitalized, a 
15-year-old girl, was in fair condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside Heritage, the campus was a picture of calm as a platoon  
of groundskeepers with weed whackers and riding mowers were the 
only break in the silence. 
</P>
<P>
	Students said that investigators had left bags on classroom  
floors and coats on chairs, general disarray that contributed to 
their unease. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was weird, knowing what happened just 48 hours ago,'' Fawn  
DeRosia, 17, said after getting her books. ``I'm shaking right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the victims, Cania Cullins, 15, was released Saturday  
from Rockdale Hospital where she had been treated for a bullet 
wound in the back of her knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated in a wheelchair with a gold Winnie the Pooh bear on her  
lap, a gift from her pastor, Miss Cullins said she has no animosity 
toward Thomas Solomon Jr., the 15-year-old suspect charged in the 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do forgive him,'' Miss Cullins said at a brief news  
conference, sitting beside her mother. ``I'll keep him in my 
prayers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Understanding didn't come so easily for senior Bonnie Jones, who  
described her school's mood as ``very melancholy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still angry,'' Miss Jones said after collecting papers she  
needed for a class. ``This kid came in and took away the last day 
of my senior year. I worked 13 years for this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	School administrators have made finals exams optional. Many  
students said they anticipate the school's reopening Monday will be 
a time of tears, hugs and consolation. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Cullins' church, Church in the Now, celebrates its 14th  
anniversary Sunday. Miss Cullins was to be the star parishioner, 
arriving at the services in a stretch limousine dispatched for her 
by the church's pastor, Bishop Jim Swilley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just excited I'm not planning a funeral,'' Swilley said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
