<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Severinsen Firm on Departing Pops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Three weeks of negotiations have failed to  
change Doc Severinsen's mind about quitting the Buffalo 
Philharmonic Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	The former leader of the Tonight Show Band, citing a dispute  
with management, quit last month after seven seasons as conductor 
of the orchestra's Pops program. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were some issues beyond both Doc's and the BPO's control  
which simply could not be resolved,'' Robert Greene, chairman of 
the Orchestra Society, told The Buffalo News. 
</P>
<P>
	Severinsen said last month that his differences began when the  
orchestra's new executive director, Lawrence Ribits, said he wanted 
to replace two consultants who marketed Severinsen's popular 
concerts last year with an in-house marketing director. 
</P>
<P>
	The consultants, Linda Schineller and Paula Blanchard, resigned  
at the end of April. Severinsen followed suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
