<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Candidate Gore Addresses Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told University of  
New Hampshire graduates today to heal their communities and work 
hard to prevent violence. 
</P>
<P>
	During speeches at the university, and later at Dover High  
School, Gore was riding high on his tie-breaking vote in the Senate 
on Thursday to tighten gun control measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just a couple of days ago I cast a tie-breaking vote,'' he  
told the invitation-only audience of about 100 people at Dover High 
before being cut off by applause. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, now awaiting House action, expands criminal background  
checks to include firearm purchases made at gun shows and 
pawnshops. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said that although guns are not solely responsible for  
school violence, their danger cannot be ignored. Pupils no longer 
settle their differences with just fist fights, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If kids are mad enough, it's easy to get access to guns,''  
Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents and students in Dover are all too well aware of what  
happens when teen-agers aren't able to control themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his efforts to tighten gun control laws, Gore said  
people hoping to stop school violence must not focus exclusively on 
guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The two boys who shot and killed 12 fellow students, a teacher  
and themselves in Colorado were influenced by hateful and violent 
messages, Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that the average American high school graduate has seen  
roughly 20,000 murders on television and in films. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of (those images) take root and bear bitter fruit,'' Gore  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But parents have powerful tools to help battle the blitz of  
media images of violence, he said, including Internet filtering 
programs and the television V-chip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
