<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Marks 50 Yrs. As Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Few nations have matched Germany's achievements of  
the last 50 years. Destroyed physically, economically and morally 
by World War II, the nation rebuilt itself as one of the West's 
strongest democracies and economies. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Germany celebrates 50 years as a democratic Federal  
Republic on Monday, half a century's successes are being 
overshadowed by events of the past two months: The decision to 
deploy fighter pilots in the air campaign against Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	An overwhelming 75 percent of Germans say they are happy with  
how their country has turned out. But their pride is being muted by 
a strain in German society over the bombing campaign and the 
memories it evokes of Hitler's brutal war. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, one of Europe's strongest  
backers of the air campaign, acknowledges the conflicting emotions 
caused by Germany's evolving role in world conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pride in our constitution, in our beloved democracy, in  
the economic, social and cultural achievements of our citizens must 
not blind us to the fact that our country faces difficult 
challenges,'' Schroeder said in a statement released ahead of 
Monday's celebrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Germany has a growing international responsibility to new,  
painful decisions and important tasks,'' he said. ``The Kosovo 
crisis is not the first to show that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pundits say Germany's participation in the NATO attacks mark a  
return to ``normalcy'' after decades at the fringes of power. 
Indeed, evidence of Germany's achievements are in abundance as the 
nation marks 50 years of postwar democracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Across from the Reichstag, where the republic's founding will be  
celebrated Monday, steel girders outlining the new chancellory 
herald the capital's rebirth in a zone razed by Allied bombs during 
World War II and abandoned as a Cold War no-man's land between East 
and West Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany is surrounded completely by friends and allies for the  
first time. Its wartime enemies have become its closest allies in 
the NATO military alliance and the European Union. The German mark 
quickly grew to be one of the world's strongest currencies and was 
the model for the new euro -- which Germany is adopting with 10 
other nations. 
</P>
<P>
	No decision, however, has emphasized Germany's struggle with its  
renewed self-confidence as much as its role in the Kosovo crisis. 
Politicians increasingly cite Germany's special responsibility to 
prevent ethnic atrocities from being repeated in Europe to justify 
contributing pilots to the NATO force. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everyone accepts the argument. The Kosovo debate has  
even penetrated the election Sunday of Germany's largely ceremonial 
president in the protest candidacy of Uta Ranke-Heinemann. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranke-Heinemann, 71, is the daughter of former President Gustav  
Heinemann, and is better known as a controversial Catholic 
theologian forbidden by the Vatican from teaching because she 
questioned the virgin birth. 
</P>
<P>
	She has no chance of succeeding outgoing President Roman Herzog  
and accepted the nomination by the ex-communist Party of Democratic 
Socialism as a platform to speak out against the NATO campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's next president will in all likelihood be Johannes Rau,  
backed by both governing coalition partners. Governor of North 
Rhine-Westphalia state for nearly two decades, the 68-year-old Rau 
is running against Dagmar Schipanski, a scientist from eastern 
Germany nominated by the opposition Christian Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranke-Heinemann's outrage is rooted in her own teen-age years  
spent among the rubble left by American bombs in her native Essen. 
</P>
<P>
	Emotions suppressed then came to the surface, she said, when she  
watched the Persian Gulf War and now the Yugoslav attacks play out 
on television. 
</P>
<P>
	While she will attend the election at the Reichstag on Sunday,  
she declined an official invitation to attend a ceremony marking 
the Federal Republic's birth on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ashamed to celebrate 50 years as long as bombs provide  
music for the ceremony,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
