<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Strikes in Editorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia is  
working and will help establish a Europe that is peaceful, 
undivided and free, President Clinton said in an opinion piece in 
Sunday's New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has been criticized by some in Congress for limiting the  
action in the region to air strikes and for not making plans for a 
ground attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he does not rule out other military options but  
said the current strategy is working and will succeed in restoring 
the people of Kosovo to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intolerable conditions the region finds itself in today  
are the result of a decadelong campaign by Slobodan Milosevic to 
build a greater Serbia by singling out whole peoples for 
destruction because of their ethnicity and faith,'' Clinton wrote 
in an article published on the Times' op-ed page. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are haunted by the images of people driven from their  
homes, pushing the elderly in wheelbarrows, telling stories of 
relatives murdered,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO action in the region is necessary because inaction  
would have posed a risk of a wider war, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said the airstrikes have broad support in the alliance  
and afford the best opportunity to forge a long-term, positive 
relationship with Russia, which has been critical of the NATO 
action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
