<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Bombed KLA Base by Mistake  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO is saying it mistakenly hit an  
ethnic Albanian rebel base yesterday. Responding to the attack on a 
hilltop border post west of Kosovo's capital, Kosovo Liberation 
Army leader Hashim Thaci was conciliatory. Thaci told Associated 
Press Television News that despite the error, ``the NATO airstrikes 
must continue, even more intensified.'' The mistake caused at least 
one KLA death. The accidental attack was the latest in a string of 
errant strikes in the alliance's eight-week air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Freed POW Gets Heroes' Welcome  
</P>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- To the delight of cheering, flag-waving  
supporters, Army Spc. Steven Gonzales today cut down the last 
reminder that he had been held as a prisoner of war in Yugoslavia: 
the faded, weather-beaten yellow bow on a courthouse tree. ``A 
great relief,'' a grinning Gonzales declared as he took his seat of 
honor in the back of a 1963 Rolls-Royce convertible for a 
homecoming parade held today in downtown Huntsville. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Urged To Retry Steele  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jurors voted 9-3 to convict Julie Hiatt Steele  
and prosecutor Kenneth Starr should ``seriously consider'' retrying 
the case, the jury foreman said today. Jack Hawxhurst said the 
evidence that Ms. Steele lied in Starr's investigation of President 
Clinton was ``very persuasive.'' The foreman said the vote to 
convict Ms. Steele was the same on each of the three charges of 
obstruction and one count of lying to the FBI. Starr has until 
Tuesday to decide whether to seek a retrial of Ms. Steele on 
charges of falsely undercutting Kathleen Willey's story of an 
unwanted sexual advance by Clinton. The first trial ended in a 
mistrial. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Greater Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	IRVINGTON, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton pressed the House for  
swift passage of gun-control legislation. Meanwhile, Rep. Henry 
Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Panel, said that his 
panel will hold hearings on the Senate legislation Thursday, but 
that no House vote is likely until after the Memorial Day recess. 
Senators approved legislation last week that would require safety 
locks on new handguns, ban violent juveniles from purchasing a 
firearm, and stop the import of large ammunition clips. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel Warplanes Raid Lebanon  
</P>
<P>
	TYRE, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes fired missiles and  
artillery on southern Lebanon today, wounding two civilians, 
Lebanese security officials said. Israeli jets fired several 
air-to-surface missiles on a valley nine miles southeast of the 
southern port city of Tyre. The raid followed several attacks by 
the Hezbollah guerrilla group against Israeli troops in southern 
Lebanon. There were no reports of casualties in the guerrilla 
attacks. 

</P>
<P>
	Jackson: African Conflict Ignored  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Fresh from participating in Sierra Leone's  
cease-fire negotiations, the Rev. Jesse Jackson today accused the 
U.S. government and media of virtually ignoring that bloody 
conflict. Jackson, who traveled to West Africa last week as special 
envoy for the United States, said a lack of concern for Africa has 
allowed the war to be ``fought in the dark'' for seven years. 
Earlier this month Jackson helped secure the release of three 
American servicemen held captive by Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Pisa Tower Leans Less After Fixing  
</P>
<P>
	PISA, Italy (AP) -- The Leaning Tower of Pisa is leaning a little  
less thanks to an experiment aimed at making the monument settle 
better into the ground, experts said today. In February, workers 
started removing soil from under the tower's base. Going into the 
experiment, the 12th century tower leaned some 6 degrees -- 13 feet 
-- off the perpendicular. Experts reported today that the tower has 
since straightened by about one-fifth of an inch. 

</P>
<P>
	Blazers Win, Lead Jazz 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace scored 20 points and Brian  
Grant had 16 points and 15 rebounds as the Portland Trail Blazers 
defeated the Utah Jazz 97-87 today to take a 2-1 lead in their 
best-of-7 second-round series. Portland used a 19-0 run in the 
first and second quarters to take control of the game and series 
against the fading Jazz. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Strawberry in Plea Deal  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry will plead no contest to a  
felony cocaine charge and misdemeanor solicitation count in a deal 
that will spare him a criminal record, The Daily News reported 
today. Strawberry is due in court Wednesday to be arraigned for his 
April 14 arrest in Tampa where he allegedly propositioned an 
undercover policewoman. After the arrest, cocaine was found in his 
wallet. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
