<DOCNO> APW19990522.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 10:11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jesse Ventura Story' To Be Shown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- The Peacock is overriding The Body.  
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura had flatly opposed NBC's plan to  
make a TV movie on the former professional wrestler's Horatio Alger 
life story. 
</P>
<P>
	But the network stood its ground and on Sunday (May 23) at 9  
p.m. EDT will present an unauthorized canvas-to-capitol biography, 
``The Jesse Ventura Story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears they have put ratings above accuracy and honesty,''  
an angry Ventura said earlier this year. Not so, countered the 
network. NBC would ``tell his story accurately and respectfully, 
based on the public record.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And so the governor has learned another lesson of political  
office: Your life, all of it, is fair game for journalists, authors 
and Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	Like so many TV movies, ``The Jesse Ventura Story'' purports to  
be ``based on the true story.'' It begins in 1964, when Ventura is 
influenced by watching Sonny Liston box on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	The story follows his careers as Navy SEAL, bouncer, bodyguard,  
pro wrestler, wrestling announcer (after leaving the ring because 
of injuries), bad-guy actor, radio talk-show host, mayor of 
Brooklyn Park, Minn., and, since January, governor of Minnesota on 
the Reform Party ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	While NBC might be taking its chances crossing Jesse ``The  
Body'' Ventura, so too is actor Nils Allen Steward in playing The 
Guv. Depicting a famous person in a movie can either be a 
star-maker or a ticket to obscurity. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, himself a former pro wrestler, shaved off his ponytail  
and flowing mustache to look more like the smooth-headed governor. 
He appreciates the movie spotlight but says he isn't dazzled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm enjoying the whole process,'' said Stewart, 37. ``It's a  
dream come true. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have three kids and a wife, Renee, and I race horses. My  
focus is my family. This is a job. It's a fun job, but I won't die 
over it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota storyteller Garrison Keillor of ``Prairie Home  
Companion'' fame has termed Ventura ``a great big honking 
bullet-headed shovel-faced mutha who talks in a steroid growl.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who has never met Ventura, remarks: ``To achieve what  
he's achieved, he can't be a stupid guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is a big man (6 feet 4 inches and 270 pounds) with a  
handsome face and mild manner. He was born in Tucson, Ariz., and a 
year later his family moved to a small Florida town near Cape 
Canaveral. 
</P>
<P>
	During his five years at Florida State, where he studied  
business and criminology, he got into weightlifting, and with a 
healthy diet rose to 350 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wrestled professionally for five years,'' he said in an  
interview. ``But to be successful, you have to go on the road. I 
have a family, and I didn't want to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burt Reynolds gave Stewart his first acting job as a wrestler  
and bodybuilder in ``Cop and a Half'' (1993). He has played the 
same kind of roles in ``The Mask,'' ``Coneheads,'' ``The Shadow'' 
and ``Escape from L.A.'', and in TV series such as ``Mad About 
You'' and ``ER.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So is pro wrestling a sport or an entertainment?  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a form of entertainment with probably the best  
group of athletes in the world,'' Stewart said. ``Maybe some say 
it's fixed, set up beforehand. Me being ignorant of a lot of 
things, I think maybe boxing is fixed and set up beforehand. They 
just don't admit it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:38:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NRA Leader: Gun Laws Won't Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- More gun laws won't prevent school shootings  
like the recent massacre at Columbine, and those who seek further 
restrictions on firearms ultimately want to take away people's 
right to bear arms, a National Rifle Association leader said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Littleton, those two horrible kids, homicidal maniacs, they  
broke 20 federal and state gun laws,'' Wayne LaPierre, the group's 
executive vice president, told a gathering of Georgia Republicans. 
``You could have put another 50 laws on the books and they would 
have broken those, too. In the search about those who should be 
held responsible, how about blaming the people who pull the 
trigger, set off the bombs and do the killings?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly every speaker, including five announced or likely  
presidential candidates, at the two-day convention commented on 
school violence, including the latest incident in Conyers, Ga., in 
which six students were wounded Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month 13 people were killed in Littleton, Colo., by gunmen  
Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris. The pair then killed themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders had considered cutting LaPierre from the agenda  
after the Conyers shooting, but decided delegates wanted to hear 
the NRA view. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPierre warned that the gun restrictions are promoted by those  
who ``hate the Second Amendment'' and want to take the right to 
bear arms apart ``brick by brick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The National Rifle Association has a core, fundamental  
interest in eliminating any violence or any crime with firearms,'' 
said LaPierre, who received repeated applause from the convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential candidate Steve Forbes urged Americans to fight  
school violence as they would a war. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time to declare a war against violence in our schools  
and in our society,'' said the businessman and magazine publisher. 
``There are no quick fixes, no magic cures ... But we must not feel 
ourselves held hostage by the notion that we are helpless in the 
face of evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were repeated charges from speakers that the Clinton  
administration hasn't vigorously enforced existing gun laws and 
concern about the push for more restrictions such as those passed 
Thursday by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed a measure requiring the sale of safety devices  
with handguns and expand a system of background checks for firearms 
purchasers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., said the bill sent to the House offers  
simple solutions to a complex problem. Such ``simplistic, 
off-the-mark'' legislation, he said, gives parents and teachers ``a 
false sense of security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes' proposal included vigorous enforcement of existing laws;  
increasing discipline in schools, reinforcing values such as 
honesty and faith in schools, and helping parents have more 
responsibility for their children with school choice and 
``educational freedom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is it easier to bring a swastika into our schools than the  
Holy Bible?'' Forbes asked the delegates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:41:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blazers Play Jazz Today in Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- With one missed shot, the Utah Jazz  
watched their homecourt advantage evaporate against the Portland 
Trail Blazers. Another loss, and Utah's championship homes will be 
put in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, they have played a lot better overall than we have in  
this series,'' Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said as Utah prepared for 
today's Game 3. ``We're going to have to improve a whole lot to 
compete up there, or they're going to have to get a lot worse, and 
I don't think that's likely to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Stockton's missed drive at the end of Game 2 Thursday night  
let the Blazers escape Utah with an 84-81 victory that evened the 
best-of-7 Western Conference semifinals 1-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The win, which came after Portland nearly blew a fourth-quarter  
lead for the second time in the series, also boosted the Blazers' 
already abundant confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not go into Utah saying to ourselves, `How are we going  
to win? Can we win?' '' Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy said Friday 
after winning the NBA Coach of the Year award. ``We believed that 
we could win. We know we can win every game we play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portland won 22 of the 25 games it played at home during the  
regular season, with one of those losses coming to the Jazz in 
mid-March, 91-77. In the playoffs, Utah has lost its last seven 
games in Portland. Its last win here was in a first-round series in 
1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no doubt we can win one or two of those games up  
there, if we don't turn the ball over and play the kind of defense 
we're capable of,'' Stockton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers led 73-64 with 5:13 to play before the Jazz rallied  
behind Stockton and Jeff Hornacek. Their consecutive 3-pointers 
closed Utah to 82-81 with 12 seconds left. Portland's Greg Anthony 
made one of two free throws with 10 seconds left, setting up 
Stockton's miss. It appeared that he might have been fouled by Jim 
Jackson, but the officials let the play stand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the shot we wanted,'' Stockton said. ``I just should  
have made it. We don't make excuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sometimes hot-headed Blazers kept their cool, unlike Tuesday  
night's opener, in which Rasheed Wallace was called for a flagrant 
foul on Bryon Russell. Wallace threw a tantrum, was called for a 
technical, and the Jazz scored four points on the possession to tie 
the game at 78-all. They didn't trail again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there was a lot of growing up that happened,'' Blazers  
power forward Brian Grant said of Game 2. ``We wanted the Jazz to 
have to beat us with their offense, or for them to have to do 
something spectacular. Which they almost did, with all the 
3-pointers they hit down the backstretch. But we were able to hold 
them off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Grant said the Blazers planned in today's game to exploit their  
quickness advantage in the paint, even though Utah center Greg 
Ostertag has played better this series after a poor opening round 
against Sacramento. In Game 1 against the Blazers, he had six 
points and six rebounds, and he grabbed 14 rebounds Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greg has had two pretty good games, which is nice because  
Arvydas Sabonis is a tough matchup for him,'' Jazz coach Jerry 
Sloan said. ``He's being conscientious about his rebounding, and 
he's doing some good things on defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz have to play better against Isaiah Rider, who continued  
his playoff surge with a career postseason high 27 points Thursday 
night. He's averaging 19.8 points in the playoffs, and is taxing 
the Jazz defense by hitting from the outside and driving the ball 
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know, I thought I played pretty good defense,''  
Hornacek said. ``I don't know how much more we could have done, 
unless it was making somebody else take the shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karl Malone, third in the league in playoff scoring at 23.9,  
behind only Allen Iverson (28.5) and Shaquille O'Neal (25.8), said 
the Jazz can't repeat their 18-turnover performance if they hope to 
win in Portland and take back homecourt advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``We put ourselves in a hole, and now we have to dig ourselves  
out,'' he said. ``You can't be intimidated now. They came into our 
place, they wanted to get a game, and they did. Now we have to go 
to their place. To win it, we have to win on their floor.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:41:02 </DATE_TIME>
