<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montana Enjoys Cutting-Horse Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Cows 1. Former San Francisco 49ers'  
quarterback Joe Montana 0. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking part in a cutting-horse demonstration Friday to help kick  
off the 1999 Pacific Coast Cutting Horse Association Derby Classic 
and Challenge, the four-time Super Bowl champ proved he can ride a 
fast-moving, quick-turning cattle horse. But this time the cows 
were just a little faster. 
</P>
<P>
	The object of the competition is for a horse and rider to  
``cut'' a cow out of herd and keep it from returning. Montana got 
interested in cutting in 1994, watching friend and former Kansas 
City Chiefs tight end Jonathan Hayes compete in Fort Worth, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, ``OK, it'll probably be fun to watch, but it was a  
lot more exciting than I even imagined,'' Montana said. ``If people 
like horses at all, once you've tried it, you're hooked.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 06:21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toshiba Develops Thin Semiconductor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Toshiba Corp. has developed a paper-thin  
computer chip that will help efforts to make ever-smaller 
electronic goods, a news report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The .0052 inch-thick semiconductor, which the company claims is  
the thinnest and lightest in the world, will mainly be used in 
memory cards, Kyodo News Agency said Saturday, quoting company 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Toshiba plans to start shipment of the semiconductors in  
mid-2000, Kyodo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Hitachi Ltd. announced it had developed a  
semiconductor called the PLEDM chip that can pack information into 
a smaller space than conventional dynamic random access memory 
chips. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
