<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Wins Heart-Surgery Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The family of a 7-year-old Oregon boy left  
blind, mute and paralyzed after a heart operation six years ago has 
won a $15.2 million malpractice suit. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury agreed Friday that a botched operation at Children's  
Hospital of Philadelphia caused permanent brain damage in Alec 
Sears. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's parents, Mark and Vicki Sears, sued the hospital,  
surgeon Dr. Marshall L. Jacobs and a hospital technician, 
contending Jacob's team cooled their son's temperature too rapidly 
before the May 1993 operation, causing permanent neurological 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The child, born with a heart defect, was 18 months old at the  
time. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury assigned Jacobs the majority of blame for the boy's  
injuries, while the hospital and technician were held less 
responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	Hospital attorney Allan H. Starr said he planned to appeal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
