<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Villages Flooded in Bavarian Alps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARMISCH-PARTENKIRCHEN, Germany (AP) -- Heavy rain in the  
Bavarian Alps sent streams over their banks, cutting off villages, 
roads and electricity to several towns, police said Saturday. At 
least three people were reported dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said a 75-year-old man who entered his basement in  
Garmisch to get rubber boots drowned when a gush of water slammed 
the door behind him trapping him in the celler. 
</P>
<P>
	A sudden burst of water from a flooded stream in Dirlewang in  
the Unterallgaeu district also trapped and drowned an 87-year-old 
man in the basement of his home in that village, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding was also reported in neighboring Switzerland to the  
south in the Lake Constance region. A German tourist died when he 
was buried by a landslide in Switzerland's Uri district, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavarian police said the worst flooding was reported around the  
village of Eschenlohe on the Loisach river, about halfway between 
Garmisch-Partenkirchen and Murnau, where military trucks that had 
driven in to deliver sand sacks were trapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Other towns hit by the flooding included Oberstdorf, Immenstadt,  
Sonthofen and the Walser Valley region, where electricity was shut 
off after a transformer station was inundated with water. 
</P>
<P>
	Emergency teams used boats to rescue scores of people from cars  
trapped and stalled on flooded roads. Several cars were swept away 
by the churning water, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Streams in the entire northern Alpine region, including the  
Iller, Wertach, Lech, Ammer, Loisach, Isar and Inn were flooded, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Austria to the east, the A14 super highway and connecting  
roads were declared impassible at several locations due to 
flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters predicted the rain would let up in the next day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 10:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Orders Boeing 727s Inspected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Aviation Administration has  
ordered emergency tests on tubes that carry electric wires through 
the fuel tanks of Boeing 727s. 
</P>
<P>
	Worried that a mixture of fuel, air and electricity could spark  
an explosion, the FAA issued its directive Friday after workers 
found severe wear on wires and holes in the tubing on two of the 
jets. Mechanics also discovered signs of electric sparking around 
the wires. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA ordered inspections last May of a similar area of the  
727's cousin, the Boeing 737. 
</P>
<P>
	That order came after mechanics found both exposed wires and  
holes in the fuel-pump conduit on a 737. The chafing was believed 
caused by engine vibration, the holes by electric sparks. About the 
same time, the agency ordered similar inspections for Boeing 747s 
and 767s. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials believe such conditions may have been behind the  
explosion that brought down TWA Flight 800. While investigators 
still do not know what caused that Boeing 747 to explode off Long 
Island in July 1996, killing the 230 people aboard, they suspect 
electricity ignited fumes in the center fuel tank. 
</P>
<P>
	The new inspections were triggered by findings of inspections on  
two 727s with more than 50,000 hours of flight time apiece. 
Mechanics found wear on wiring used to power in-tank fuel pumps and 
signs of electric arcing. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA ordered airlines to inspect the boost pump area for any  
sign that fuel was leaking into aluminum tubes that carry the fuel 
pump wires. On Friday, the 727's manufacturer, Seattle-based Boeing 
Co., issued a separate notice to 727 operators outlining ways to 
test the pipes and repair the wires. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA order did not immediately require wiring inspections or  
repairs, just an inspection of the tubing for leaks and necessary 
repairs. The agency said it planned to require additional 
examination of the wiring after more information becomes available. 
</P>
<P>
	The order gives airlines five days to perform the tests on 727s  
with more than 50,000 hours of flight time. On planes with less 
flight time, the tests must be made within 10 days or before a 
plane accumulates 30,000 hours of flight time, whichever is later. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 1,461 Boeing 727s worldwide, 1,081 are operated by U.S.  
carriers, Boeing spokesman Bill Seil said. The problem was 
discovered during a routine maintenance check of freight carriers 
in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA officials were unclear whether the order would affect the  
traveling public. About one-third of the planes involved are cargo 
carriers, and the inspections can be spread between five and 10 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing spokesman Seil said: ``We see it as a reason to inspect  
the planes. It shouldn't be a disruption to services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing and FAA officials estimated that the tests would take  
about four hours per aircraft and cost $252,000 for the U.S. fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of foreign-registered aircraft are not compelled to  
conduct the tests, but foreign civil aviation authorities tend to 
follow FAA safety recommendations, as the U.S. agency does with 
suggestions made abroad. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
