<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Villages Flooded in Bavarian Alps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARMISCH-PARTENKIRCHEN, Germany (AP) -- Heavy rain in the  
Bavarian Alps sent streams over their banks, cutting off villages, 
roads and electricity to several towns, police said Saturday. At 
least three people were reported dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said a 75-year-old man who entered his basement in  
Garmisch to get rubber boots drowned when a gush of water slammed 
the door behind him trapping him in the celler. 
</P>
<P>
	A sudden burst of water from a flooded stream in Dirlewang in  
the Unterallgaeu district also trapped and drowned an 87-year-old 
man in the basement of his home in that village, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flooding was also reported in neighboring Switzerland to the  
south in the Lake Constance region. A German tourist died when he 
was buried by a landslide in Switzerland's Uri district, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bavarian police said the worst flooding was reported around the  
village of Eschenlohe on the Loisach river, about halfway between 
Garmisch-Partenkirchen and Murnau, where military trucks that had 
driven in to deliver sand sacks were trapped. 
</P>
<P>
	Other towns hit by the flooding included Oberstdorf, Immenstadt,  
Sonthofen and the Walser Valley region, where electricity was shut 
off after a transformer station was inundated with water. 
</P>
<P>
	Emergency teams used boats to rescue scores of people from cars  
trapped and stalled on flooded roads. Several cars were swept away 
by the churning water, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Streams in the entire northern Alpine region, including the  
Iller, Wertach, Lech, Ammer, Loisach, Isar and Inn were flooded, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Austria to the east, the A14 super highway and connecting  
roads were declared impassible at several locations due to 
flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters predicted the rain would let up in the next day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
