<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pisa Tower Leans Less After Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PISA, Italy (AP) -- The Leaning Tower of Pisa is leaning a little  
less thanks to an experiment aimed at making the monument settle 
better into the ground, experts said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, workers started removing soil from under the  
tower's base. Going into the experiment, the 12th century tower 
leaned some 6 degrees -- 13 feet -- off the perpendicular. Experts 
reported Saturday that the tower has since straightened by about 
one-fifth of an inch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results of the experimental excavation are superior than  
the expectations,'' said Michele Jamiolkowski, who heads a 
committee of experts monitoring measures aimed at keeping the tower 
from toppling over. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the digging began, two sets of steel ``suspenders,''  
anchored to giant winches dug into the ground about 100 yards from 
the tower, were attached to the monument. 
</P>
<P>
	Should the excavation threaten to make the tower wobble, the  
suspenders would be pulled tight to stabilize it. 
</P>
<P>
	The digging will continue, but Jamiolkowski said the government  
must renew funding since the money allocated for the project is 
running out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
