<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Blacks Out 16 Yugoslav Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes roared over Belgrade  
and much of Serbia early today, blacking out the capital and 15 
other cities in a determined attempt to pressure President Slobodan 
Milosevic to agree to a peace deal for Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The widespread power outages came as NATO jets reportedly  
dropped special cluster bombs with carbon filaments that cause 
damage to wires conducting electricity, Yugoslav media reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Four missiles hit a power plant in Kolubara, 20 miles southwest  
of Belgrade, targeting its main distribution center and a nearby 
transformer station, Serb media said. That could cripple the plant 
for weeks -- a situation that will likely lead to protracted power 
shortages over a wide area. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen workers were injured in the Kolubara strike, the  
private Beta news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Repair teams managed to restore power to Belgrade early today,  
but the grid went down again a few hours later. A statement from 
Serbia's power company accused NATO of wanting to ``cause a 
humanitarian catastrophe of major proportions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other major developments:  
</P>
<P>
	-- At the Macedonian border, 3,700 refugees poured out of Kosovo,  
many saying Serb forces came to their homes, ordered them out, and 
demanded money and valuables along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In Washington, President Clinton signed a bill that authorizes  
$12 billion for the conflict with Yugoslavia to help Kosovo 
Albanian refugees, aid the neighboring Balkan countries and fund 
U.S. forces around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said NATO is  
simultaneously planning for two scenarios for Kosovo: A 
peacekeeping force of approximately 50,000 American and European 
troops in Kosovo and for the possibility that NATO would invade to 
restore order in the war-wracked province. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said today it attacked power installations, ammunition  
dumps, highway bridges and army barracks during its most intensive 
night of sorties yet. It also took advantage of good weather to 
strike a dozen tanks, 18 military vehicles and nine artillery 
positions. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 684 sorties were flown. Of that total, 245 were strike  
sorties and 90 were sorties attacking air defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Strikes continued into the day. The state-run Tanjug news agency  
said NATO fired eight missiles into the southwestern Kosovo city of 
Prizren this morning, after an earlier attack Friday night. The 
southern Serbian city of Leskovac was also struck. 
</P>
<P>
	Other targets today included a fuel depot in Belgrade's Cukarica  
district, the Batajnica military airfield northwest of Belgrade, a 
television transmitter on Mount Fruska Gora. In the far north, a 
fuel depot and an industrial zone were targeted in Sombor, Tanjug 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	To the south in Kosovo, Tanjug said at least 100 missiles were  
fired by NATO at different targets between Friday and early today. 
At least 20 people were killed, more than 50 were wounded and 
``enormous damage'' was caused, Tanjug reported. It was apparently 
counting the 19 people reported killed Friday in what Serb news 
media said was an attack on a prison in the northwestern Kosovo 
town of Istok. 
</P>
<P>
	The NATO air bombardment aims to force Milosevic to withdraw his  
40,000 Serb troops and special police from Kosovo, a province in 
Serbia, permit the return of nearly 800,000 ethnic Albanian 
refugees who have been expelled or fled, and allow NATO 
peacekeepers in to enforce the peace. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Finnish President Martti  
Ahtisaari met today in Sweden to discuss the crisis in Kosovo. 
Ahtisaari has been mentioned as a possible mediator in the crisis, 
since Finland is not a NATO member and has good relations with 
Russia, a longtime Yugoslav ally. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States says it has reports of large-scale desertions  
by Yugoslav army reservists and anti-war demonstrations by 
soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	But a Foreign Ministry spokesman said troops who returned to two  
central Serbian towns this week were just ``regular soldiers 
returning home'' as part of a reduction of Serbian forces in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Montenegrin town of Cetinje, some 5,000 people protested  
new Yugoslav army reinforcements around their city Friday and 
demanded that the military withdraw. The demonstration was the 
biggest protest against the Yugoslav army in Montenegro, which with 
Serbia makes up what is left of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
