<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trinidad, De La Hoya in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The deal for a welterweight  
unification fight between Oscar De La Hoya and Felix Trinidad is 
bogged down by a money dispute between Trinidad's father-manager 
and promoter Don King, the Puerto Rican fighter's family said 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Bob Arum, De La Hoya's promoter, said the fight is on.  
</P>
<P>
	``Don and the old man are squabbling over it,'' Arum said  
Saturday, referring to Felix Trinidad Sr. ``Don has assured me it 
will be no problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We signed the deal, King and I. The fight will happen.''  
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Arum announced the deal had been struck for De La  
Hoya to receive $15 million and Trinidad's camp to get $10.5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Not so, said Trinidad family lawyer Nicolas Medina.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's unacceptable. What King did was negotiate another  
$500,000 for himself,'' Medina told The Associated Press. ``The 
deal is stuck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said King already had agreed he would get no more than $2  
million. Under an original proposal already rejected by Felix 
Trinidad Sr., the fighter's father and manager, Trinidad's camp 
would receive $8 million and King $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	King could not be reached for comment. An answering machine at  
his office said it was closed for the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the first difference between King and Trinidad Sr., who  
lost a court case last year in which he argued the promoter no 
longer had contractual rights over his son. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed fight still would depend on De La Hoya beating Oba  
Carr in defense of his WBC title on Saturday night and Trinidad, 
the IBF champion, beating Hugo Pineda on May 29 in Puerto Rico 
</P>
<P>
	It would take place Sept. 18 in Las Vegas and would be televised  
on pay-per-view, according to Arum. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinidad Sr. said Saturday that he is demanding an additional $8  
for every cable viewer over 850,000. Trinidad has a contract with 
HBO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
