<DOCNO> APW19990522.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 09:22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young Filmmaker Experiences Cannes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- Sunup at Cannes. Cell phones start ringing  
at the seaside Hotel du Cap, home to the very biggest stars this 
fortnight. Soon, Mel Gibson, Tim Robbins, Susan Sarandon and Sean 
Connery will be toweling off and sipping their morning coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Far off, in a hostel outside Cannes, Steve Race won't be  
toweling or sipping. The 25-year-old filmmaker from Oakdale, N.Y., 
on Long Island, doesn't have towels in his Spartan room, nor can he 
afford a Riviera-priced breakfast. Cold cereal and an evening 
fast-food pizza are all the budget can handle. 
</P>
<P>
	Young, ambitious and hungry (especially around lunchtime), Race  
is experiencing a whole different Cannes from that of the stars, 
the agents, the public relations people. Armed with a print of his 
very first film and an endless supply of chutzpah, Race knows this 
festival is his big chance. And he's making the most of it. 
</P>
<P>
	A day with Steve:  
</P>
<P>
	7:30 a.m.: Steve's fellow producer, Brian, stumbles into the  
room after a night of drinking. Steve is angry at being woken up; 
he has a meeting at 10 a.m. with a producer from London. He rolls 
over and goes back to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	10:30 a.m.: Steve arrives half an hour late for the meeting,  
sweating profusely under his baseball cap. He had to run 2 1/2 miles 
to get there. No problem: He tells the producer, Beth Sanders, that 
an earlier meeting ran long. She seems to buy it. ``Besides, it 
looks good for me to seem busy,'' he says later. 
</P>
<P>
	They watch his film on a VCR. ``Labor Day,'' directed by and  
starring Steve Race, is the story of a bunch of buddies partying 
over Labor Day weekend on Fire Island -- getting together, breaking 
up, getting drunk, having sex, going home. 
</P>
<P>
	One could say it has a homemade charm. ``Casablanca'' it is not.  
</P>
<P>
	Beth tells him she's impressed with the camera work. She asks  
the budget. He dodges the question (``How could I tell her it was 
only $60,000?'' he says). 
</P>
<P>
	During the meeting, TV film critic Roger Ebert ambles by. Steve  
jumps up and introduces himself. Ebert asks: ``Do you know where I 
can buy a battery for my camera?'' 
</P>
<P>
	11:30 a.m.: Back to the hostel for a shower. Since there are no  
towels, Steve puts on his underwear and sits on the curb for 15 
minutes to dry off in the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	1 p.m.: Steve is handing out postcards and posting flyers for  
his screenings on doors all over Cannes. ``Director attending!!!'' 
the flyers say. Outside one hotel, he has another big moment: He 
runs into Tim Robbins. ``I'm Steve Race,'' he says. ``I'm a 
filmmaker, here with `Labor Day.' I'd love to work with you.'' 
Robbins says nothing. Not a word. ``Well, I still want to work with 
you,'' Steve says. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve spends the afternoon canvassing the hotels, trying to get  
film company types to come to his screenings in a small basement 
room at the festival palace. But Steve has one overriding goal: to 
snag somebody from Miramax Films. 
</P>
<P>
	3 p.m.: By sheer luck, Steve gets his chance. There is a panel  
discussion featuring Harvey Weinstein, the all-powerful head of 
Miramax, and Ebert. They open the floor for questions. Steve rises. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm Steve. I'm here with my first film, I'm 25. How do I get  
Harvey Weinstein to come check out my work?'' Applause erupts. 
Harvey laughs. Later he tells Steve: ``Don't worry, kid, I was in 
your shoes once.'' He says Miramax will look at the film. 
</P>
<P>
	5 p.m.: Steve is veering from his duties. Someone has offered  
him a chance to meet Jenna Jameson, a porn star. He can't resist. 
She tells him it's nice to meet someone so dedicated to his craft. 
She invites him to a party later. He tells her he'll put her in one 
of his next films. 
</P>
<P>
	7 p.m.: Hungry after an afternoon of work, Steve buys a loaf of  
bread and stick of butter. Sitting on the curb outside his hostel 
to eat it, he spies the owner looking at him. ``My favorite broke 
American,'' the owner says, laughing. He pulls out his empty 
pockets to illustrate the point. 
</P>
<P>
	2 a.m.: A long night of low-budget partying and networking is  
over. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EPILOGUE: As the festival draws to a close, Steve still hasn't  
found a buyer. But he's made countless connections, and things are 
looking up for ``Labor Day.'' The money has held up -- kind of. 
Weinstein kept his word and asked for a tape of the film. Steve has 
even met Prince Albert of Monaco. Best of all, Kevin Smith, the 
quirky, New Jersey-born director of ``Clerks'' and ``Chasing Amy,'' 
has watched 15 minutes of the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve says that Smith told him: ``Hey man, I really liked it, it  
was funny.'' (Smith later confirms this.) 
</P>
<P>
	For Steve, that moment is the highlight of the festival.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 02:41:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies GM Puts Heat on Schilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Now stepping into the batter's box against  
Curt Schilling: Philadelphia Phillies general manager Ed Wade. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days after Schilling demanded that the Phillies spend more  
money or trade him, Wade distributed a two-page, point-by-point 
rebuttal Friday in which he said Schilling was ``self-serving'' and 
``wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Curt has a right to express his opinions,'' Wade said. ``But  
that's all they are. Much of what Curt says is irresponsible, and 
his comments often are not based upon facts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every fifth day, Curt has the opportunity to go out and be a  
horse on the mound. Unfortunately, on the other four days, he tends 
to say things which are detrimental to the club and clearly 
self-serving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Schilling was the guest on major league baseball's  
weekly conference call with the national media. As Wade pointed out 
in his statement, ``Baseball uses the call to promote the game and 
its star players. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, Curt used the call as a forum to discuss the  
Phillies' finances, the team's ownership group and his personal 
feelings about the direction of the club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Did he ever.  
</P>
<P>
	``For us to be successful and to compete and to win, they're  
going to have to go out and get a big player. We're short right 
now,'' Schilling said. ``They told us they're not ready to pay in 
the Randy Johnson financial territory. If they signed Randy Johnson 
this winter, would we be contenders? If you bring in Randy Johnson, 
Brad Radke, Kenny Rogers, you name it, we'd be a legitimate 
contender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling met with team president David Montgomery on Thursday  
night during the team's exhibition game against its Triple-A 
affiliate in Moosic, Pa. Montgomery did not return a call Friday, 
and Wade said he was told it was a ``private meeting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think that it's necessary for me to schedule a time to  
meet with him,'' Wade said. ``I'm finished with it. I said hello to 
him last night, and he said hello to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies began the season with a $30.36 million payroll, the  
fourth lowest in the National League. Despite that, the Phillies 
were 21-18 Friday, trailing NL East leader Atlanta by 3 1/2 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Curt had a chance to promote his own performance and that of  
his teammates,'' Wade said. ``He had a chance to talk about Mike 
Lieberthal, Scott Rolen, Doug Glanville, Paul Byrd, and others. And 
maybe he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling did praise some teammates, notably pitcher Carlton  
Loewer, saying the right-hander is ``going to be an impact 
pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But all the positives he could have gotten out of that forum  
were negated by his comments about areas in which he is 
uninformed,'' Wade said. ``It's unfortunate that he chose to use 
the spotlight and do something other than put his best foot 
forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling, off to a 7-1 start, has a complete no-trade clause in  
his contract, which pays him $10.8 million this year and next with 
an option for 2001 at $6.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	He has said repeatedly he is willing to waive the clause to be  
traded to a contender, and frequently turns postgame interviews 
into impromptu rip sessions directed toward Montgomery and chairman 
Bill Giles. After beating Kevin Brown and the Dodgers on May 2, 
Schilling said, ``It's been six years since we've played good 
baseball on a consistent basis here. It's up to the Phillies 
ownership to get the players and put a good team out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What message does that comment send to his teammates?'' Wade  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the conference call Wednesday, Schilling elaborated on his  
comments in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're knocking on the door and they stand pat, I'd want to  
go,'' Schilling said. ``If ownership is not willing to make a trade 
or spend in July, they need to sell the team and give the 
Philadelphia fans what they deserve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wade declined to expound on his statement. Some excerpts:  
</P>
<P>
	--On acquiring more pitching: ``We've been trying to upgrade our  
rotation since the end of last season and will continue to try. We 
haven't turned down any trade for starting pitchers because of 
dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On Schilling's belief that Forbes Magazine's report that the  
Phillies made a profit in 1998 was correct, and the team's 
assertion that it lost money was not: ``I've been in all the 
ownership group's meetings since December 1997, and I've seen the 
bottom line. The team has lost significant dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--On Schilling's trade demand: ``Curt does not have a `trade me'  
clause. He has a `no trade' clause, which means he can refuse to be 
traded to any team. If we ever decide we want to trade Curt, he'll 
have his say. But Curt does not have the total say in this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wade insisted that the controversy would ``absolutely not''  
affect a decision to trade his ace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:36:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NASCAR's Stewart Qualifies for Indy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tony Stewart pulled off the track and kept  
going. 
</P>
<P>
	As soon as the former Indy Racing League champion qualified for  
the Indianapolis 500 on Saturday, he departed with a police escort 
to the airport for a 600-mile flight to Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours and four minutes later, Stewart was on the track at  
Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., practicing for Saturday 
night's NASCAR Winston Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a lot of good people helping me, taking care of  
things,'' Stewart said on the way to the airport from the 
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, where he qualified at an average 
220.653 mph. ``If you want to know, this is a lot more relaxing 
than my four-lap qualifying run just was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart started from the pole as a rookie in 1996. He started  
fifth and finished second in 1997 and started fourth last year, 
when he was the first out because of engine failure. He left Team 
Menard this season to drive fulltime for Joe Gibbs Racing in the 
NASCAR Winston Cup series but formed his own team in order to still 
race at Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to drive in the May 30 race here, then take another  
quick flight to Concord for the Coca Cola 600 that night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to go quicker, obviously, but we were flat-out the  
whole way around. That's all the car had today,'' Stewart said of 
his qualification run. ``We got through this part of it. We just 
have to wait and see what everybody else does from here on in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who comes from nearby Columbus, Ind., received a  
rousing reception from the fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was unbelievable. It makes you feel good,'' he said. ``I  
know there were a lot of upset people when I left the IRL. I didn't 
want to have to leave, but I felt like it was something I needed to 
do for my career. It was the right decision to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MAKE MY DAY:* Thursday will be ``Arie Luyendyk Day'' in  
Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Stephen Goldsmith will visit the track that day, the final  
two hours of practice before the race, and will present Luyendyk 
with a proclamation and the key to the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indy is not just another race. Everything around Indy, the  
city, the history. It's just a special event,'' said the 
45-year-old Luyendyk, who is retiring after the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I can enjoy it just as much as a spectator as I will  
as a driver. I'm going to keep enjoying Indy, just in a different 
way,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO COMPETITION:* Twenty years ago, Howdy Holmes had no  
competition for Indy 500 rookie of the year -- literally. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes was the only first-year driver in the race, the first  
time since 1939 that only one rookie qualified. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in college at the time and kind of pursued that, ended  
up getting a small Formula Ford and doing all the work myself,'' 
Holmes said Saturday, recalling his start in auto racing. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing led to another and I worked my way here and was very  
lucky all six times that I competed here. So it means a great deal 
to me to have sat in the stands, been a race car driver and to come 
back and see all the people, who are warm and friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes started 13th and finished seventh as a rookie and drove  
in five more races at Indy from 1982-88. His best finish was sixth 
in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Since his appearance as the only rookie, the fewest first-year  
starters in the race were three in 1990, with Eddie Cheever, Scott 
Goodyear and Dean Hall. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DRIVERS OUT:* John Paul Jr., who led 39 laps in his seventh  
Indy start last year, and rookie Dave Steele were scratched from 
qualifications because of injuries in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul, who injured his back in a crash on Friday, was released  
from Methodist Hospital Saturday. Car owner Jonathan Byrd replaced 
Paul with Andy Michner, who was eighth as a rookie last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was disappointing, our whole year's efforts out the window  
here,'' Paul said. ``It's a day-to-day thing. They're going to look 
at me in the morning. Right now, every time I turn my head side to 
side, it's like your eyes are slow to follow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steele, who suffered a mild concussion and a back sprain in a  
crash on Wednesday, returned to the track on Friday but was unable 
to drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hit at 82 Gs and pulled everything in his upper body. He  
can hardly pick up a pencil right now,'' Panther Racing's John 
Barnes said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OUTDOES DAD:* John Hollansworth Jr. managed something his  
father never did -- qualify for the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Hollansworth came to Indy in 1967 but never made a  
qualifying attempt because his car owner loaned his engine to 
another race team. On Saturday, as he watched from trackside, his 
son finally put a Hollansworth in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't thought about that too much. I'm sure that will sink  
in later,'' the younger Hollansworth said of his family history at 
Indy. ``I'm just happy to get in the field safely on the first day 
and not have to sweat it tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rookie driver qualified with a four-lap average of 221.698  
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys really made a great call on the car ... kind of got  
me dialed in on that last warmup session so we had good balance,'' 
he said. ``I think we pretty much ran flat all the way around, on 
the last three laps anyway. It's just great to be here.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:36:02 </DATE_TIME>
