<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrant Held for 9 Years by INS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- An Ethiopian Jew held by U.S. Immigration officials  
for nine years while fighting deportation was released on parole 
pending a review of his case. 
</P>
<P>
	Lulseged Dhine was freed on Friday from Krome Detention Center  
west of Miami and was flown to Arizona to be released into the 
custody of friends there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling disbelief,'' Dhine said. ``It's been nine years  
and 45 days. With all the ups and downs, I'm very grateful to so 
many people who helped me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dhine has said he will be persecuted as a Jew if he is returned  
to Ethiopia. 
</P>
<P>
	He is awaiting a hearing on an application for relief under the  
United Nations Convention Against Torture, which prevents the 
deportation of any individual who would face torture upon return to 
a country. 
</P>
<P>
	He can apply for employment authorization, and must keep INS  
informed of his whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to finally free him ``fit under law and regulations  
that provide for the release of individuals on a case-by-case basis 
for humanitarian reasons,'' said INS spokesman Michael Gilhooly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have determined that Mr. Dhine poses neither a risk to the  
public or a risk of flight at this time,'' Gilhooly said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dhine was a legal refugee when he fled to the United States in  
1978 at age 14 after his family was killed because of their Jewish 
faith under the Marxist regime of Mengistu Haile Mariam. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s, Dhine was convicted of seven misdemeanors, four of  
them drug-related -- including possession of marijuana. He served a 
total of several months in jail, at different times. 
</P>
<P>
	After his final conviction in 1990, the INS revoked his legal  
status and started deportation proceedings against him. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled in April 1993 that Dhine should be given  
asylum, but that decision was overturned on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Dhine's case was covered by the 1996 Illegal Immigration Reform  
and Immigrant Responsibility Act, which requires all noncitizens 
convicted of certain crimes be detained by the INS for deportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 07:41:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Gets Stake in Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The largest-ever hostile corporate takeover in  
Europe has apparently succeeded, with Olivetti today formally 
accepting shares amounting to a 51 percent stake in Italian 
telecommunications giant Telecom. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a board meeting today, Olivetti, a typewriter and  
computer manufacturer-turned-telecommunications company, announced 
it will accept the shares collected during its hostile takeover 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Olivetti acquired 67 percent or more of Telecom, it would  
have accepted the tendered shares automatically. Below that level 
it reserved the right to accept or refuse them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The boards of Olivetti and Tecnost have decided to accept the  
shares tendered in the offer and Olivetti will go ahead with its 
industrial plan for TI,'' Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto 
Colaninno, told reporters today at company headquarters near Milan, 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Tecnost is the Olivetti unit used as the vehicle for the  
takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian stock market officials said late Friday in Milan that  
Olivetti had secured a majority stake, clearing the way for the 
completion of the hostile $64 billion takeover of Italy's No. 1 
phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Olivetti had less than 20 percent of Telecom's  
shares. But on the final day for securing shareholder backing for 
its upstart effort, most of Telecom Italia's strongest supporters 
jumped ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno said today that the management handover will take  
place between ``gentlemen,'' in an absolutely ``friendly manner'' 
and not in the courts. He was expected to meet with his counterpart 
at Telecom, Franco Bernabe, on Monday when the transition phases 
will be mapped out. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno said the possibility of a merger of Tecnost and  
Telecom will be the subject of many long discussions in the coming 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Colaninno issued a statement saying he was ``proud of  
the market response to our offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The positive conclusion ... signals the beginning of a new,  
great industrial history,'' Colaninno said. 
</P>
<P>
	The result surpassed the 35 percent threshold that Olivetti said  
it needed to press ahead with its plan to acquire Italy's former 
government-run telephone monopoly for $12.15 per share at current 
exchange rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with a majority stake in Telecom, he is almost certain to  
push ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Colaninno has put a lot into this, and he's not going to back  
out,'' said Dwayne Taylor, an analyst at the London-based Robert 
Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the biggest disappointments for Telecom were the  
defections of almost all of its core shareholders, an investor 
group organized when Telecom was privatized in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Assicurazioni Generali, Italy's largest insurer, said it  
tendered all its Telecom shares, equal to 1 percent of the total 
number outstanding, while San Paulo IMI, a bank, turned over 0.8 
percent. Another bank, Unicredito, tendered 0.7 percent of 
Telecom's shares, and IFIL, the holding company of Italy's Agnelli 
industrial dynasty, gave up 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one core shareholder, Credit Suisse Group, said it would  
stick with Telecom's current management. 



