<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Tests Ordered on 727s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concerned that a mixture of fuel, air and  
electricity could spark an explosion, the Federal Aviation 
Administration has ordered emergency tests on the tubes that carry 
electrical wires through the fuel tanks on Boeing 727s. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA directive came after workers found severe wear on the  
wires and holes in the tubing on two of the jets. Mechanics also 
discovered signs of electrical sparking around the wires. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA ordered inspections last May on a similar area of the  
727's cousin, the Boeing 737. 
</P>
<P>
	That order came after mechanics found both exposed wires and  
holes in the fuel-pump conduit on a 737. The chafing was believed 
to have been caused by engine vibration and the holes were believed 
to have been caused by electrical sparks. 
</P>
<P>
	About the same time, the agency also ordered similar inspections  
for Boeing 747s and 767s. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials are concerned that a cocktail of fuel, air and  
electricity could spark an explosion such as that which downed TWA 
Flight 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators still do not know what caused the plane, a Boeing  
747, to explode off Long Island in July 1996, killing all 230 
people aboard. They suspect fumes in the center fuel tank were 
ignited by electricity. Since then, they have been examining the 
wiring configurations on similar planes and ordering inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``telegraphic airworthiness directive'' issued by the agency  
on Friday was triggered by the findings of inspections on two 727s 
with over 50,000 hours of flight time. 
</P>
<P>
	Mechanics found wear on wiring used to power in-tank fuel pumps  
and signs of electrical arcing as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``This wear and arc-through condition has been attributed to  
chafing between the in-tank fuel boost pump wiring and the wall of 
the surrounding conduit,'' the agency told 727 operators. ``This 
condition, if not corrected, could result in ignition of fuel 
vapors in a fuel tank and a fuel tank explosion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA ordered airlines to inspect the boost pump area for any  
sign that fuel was leaking into the aluminum tubes that carry the 
fuel pump wires. On Friday, the 727's manufacturer, the 
Seattle-based Boeing Co., issued a separate notice to 727 operators 
outlining ways to test the pipes and repair the wires. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA order did not immediately require any wiring inspections  
or repairs -- just an inspection of the tubing for leaks and any 
necessary repairs to it. The agency said it planned to require 
additional examination of the wiring after more information becomes 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	The order gives airlines five days to perform the tests on 727s  
with more than 50,000 hours of flight time. On planes with less 
flight time, the tests must be made within 10 days or before a 
plane accumulates 30,000 hours of flight time, whichever is later. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 1,461 Boeing 727s worldwide, of which 1,081 are  
operated by U.S. carriers, according to Boeing spokesman Bill Seil. 
The problem was discovered during a routine maintenance check of 
freight carriers in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	FAA officials were unclear what effect the order would have on  
the traveling public, since about one-third of the planes were 
cargo carriers and the inspections could be spread between five and 
10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly hope the impact will be limited, but we can't be  
sure,'' said FAA spokesman Les Dorr. 
</P>
<P>
	Seil, the Boeing spokesman, said: ``We see it as a reason to  
inspect the planes. It shouldn't be a disruption to services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing and FAA officials estimated that the tests would take  
about four hours per aircraft and cost a total of $252,000 for the 
U.S. fleet. 
</P>
<P>
	Operators of foreign-registered aircraft are not compelled to  
conduct the tests, but foreign civil aviation authorities tend 
follow FAA safety recommendations, as the agency does with 
suggestions made aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	The 727-100, a tri-jet, first entered service in 1964. A longer  
fuselage version, the 727-200, entered service in 1967, with the 
last delivery being made in September 1984. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
