<HEADLINE> Pantani Takes Lead in Italy Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	L'AQUILA, Italy (AP) -- Defending champion Marco Pantani broke  
away from the lead group on the final climb Saturday and easily won 
the eighth stage of the Tour of Italy to take the overall lead in 
the cycling race. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani made his move with about a mile left on the windy,  
snow-lined mountain road to the finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Gotti, the 1997 winner, was the only rider who tried to  
follow, but he could not match hi fellow Italian's climbing prowess 
in the fog and 37-degree weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani was all alone at the finish line at Gran Sasso D'Italia,  
at an altitude of 2,343 feet. He covered the 157 miles from Pescara 
in 7 hours, 9 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain's Jose Maria Jimenez was 23 seconds behind, followed by  
Alex Zuelle and Gotti. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory pushed Pantani atop the overall standings, replacing  
Frenchman Laurent Jalabert. 
</P>
<P>
	Jalabert finished 1:05 behind Pantani on Saturday and fell to  
fifth in the standings, 55 seconds off the pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
