<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 02:31:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Club Voting on Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- An icon of the Sierra Club is again seeking  
to lead the century-old environmental group, but considers himself 
a longshot for the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, I don't see enough votes. I'm afraid I'll miss  
again,'' said 86-year-old David Brower. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of the Sierra Club were to vote today on whether to  
re-elect President Chuck McGrady or replace him with Brower. 
</P>
<P>
	Brower says he's running as the voice of change and wants to  
energize a 550,000-member organization that he claims has become 
preoccupied with procedure and afraid to take chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's practically no talk about what's happening to Earth,''  
he told the San Francisco Examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	Brower, who served as executive director of the club for 17  
years, led the organization decades ago to a series of major 
victories, including influencing the creation of nine national 
parks and seashores, and preventing the damming of the Grand 
Canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	But 30 years ago, the 15-member board, of which he is now a  
member, fired him after he made some decisions without consulting 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	McGrady, who runs a summer camp in North Carolina and beat  
Brower last year, said he doesn't think he and Brower are that far 
apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a lot of differences in our values,'' he said. ``I  
don't think anything I support he would be against.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brower's candidacy has not been greeted with universal applause  
-- there is some feeling the club has been run well in recent years 
and is heading in the right direction. 
</P>
<P>
	The fact that he may not be elected ``is unfortunate and in no  
way meant to minimize his accomplishments,'' said director Betsy 
Gaines of Bozeman, Mont. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Chad Hanson of Pasadena, a founder of the John Muir  
Sierrans, a subculture of the club that eschews compromise on major 
environmental issues, remains confident that Brower is just what 
the club needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This board sees itself as an administrator and is more  
concerned with governance and process than anything else,'' Hanson 
said. ``It should be out there leading, with proactive, visible 
campaigns. David offers that kind of leadership and it's 
unfortunate (that he may not get the chance).'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
