<DOCNO> APW19990522.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 03:31:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paralyzed Gymnast Visits U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Chinese gymnast Sang Lan, who was  
paralyzed during the Goodwill Games last summer, fulfilled a 
longtime wish by visiting the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Accompanied by China's U.N. Ambassador Qin Huasun and a host of  
diplomats, the 17-year-old gymnast on Friday got to see the U.N. 
Security Council chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.N. symbolizes world peace,'' Sang said through an  
interpreter. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in a wheelchair, she also got to see Chinese sculptures  
and other gifts to the United Nations from her government. 
</P>
<P>
	Sang, a member of the Chinese national team, was injured during  
a warmup exercise at the Goodwill Games last summer in Uniondale, 
N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	She was paralyzed from the neck down, but has regained some  
strength in her shoulders, elbows and wrists, and can raise her 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	China's U.N. Mission said the visit was her last public  
appearance in the United States before returning home Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
