<HEADLINE> Jackson: African Conflict Ignored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Fresh from participating in Sierra Leone's  
cease-fire negotiations, the Rev. Jesse Jackson today accused the 
U.S. government and media of virtually ignoring that bloody 
conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who traveled to West Africa last week as special envoy  
for the United States, said a lack of concern for Africa has 
allowed the war to be ``fought in the dark'' for seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We jumped in to protect the Albanians being driven out of  
Kosovo, but Africans have to defend themselves,'' Jackson told 
reporters at his Rainbow/PUSH Coalition headquarters in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month Jackson helped secure the release of three  
American servicemen held captive by Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson also blasted the Western media for neglecting its  
obligation to shed light on the situation in Sierra Leone, while 
covering every inch of the crisis in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	He called for increased aid to Sierra Leone, arguing that the  
country's soldiers have little incentive to stop fighting because 
the army is their only source of food and money. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson and representatives from the United Nations and the  
Organization of African Unity convinced President Ahmed Tejan 
Kabbah and Foday Sankoh, leader of the Revolutionary United Front, 
to sign an agreement to lay down their weapons on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks are to start the following day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
