<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Peanut Growers Debate Promotion Fee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Peanut growers begin voting Monday on whether  
to assess themselves a fee to help promote their product. The plan 
could fail because of a dispute with the Agriculture Department 
over using some of the money for research. 
</P>
<P>
	``I personally am not nearly as comfortable with it being what  
we as growers need,'' said Billy Griggs, a farmer in Dooly County, 
Ga., who is chairman of the Georgia Peanut Commission. ``We need a 
program that works for growers. I'd hoped that this would be it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilbur Gamble, chairman of the National Peanut Growers  
Association, had similar reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our board has taken a position that. . . each farmer on his  
own will make the decision. We're not saying we won't support but 
we're not out there trying to push it,'' said Gamble, who farms 160 
miles outside Atlanta. ``I personally don't think I can support 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal basically establishes a checkoff program similar to  
existing ones for everything from beef, pork, popcorn, milk and 
watermelons, in which farmers pay to help promote their product. 
</P>
<P>
	The referendum is open to all farmers who grew peanuts between  
Aug. 1, 1997, and July 30, 1998. The mail-in referendum will run 
from Monday through June 11. The Agriculture Department last week 
sent out 13,901 ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval only requires a simple majority of those farmers who  
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed assessment, equal 1 percent of the sales price of  
peanuts, would generate an estimated $10 million annually for a 
program to increase both domestic consumption and exports of 
peanuts. 
</P>
<P>
	For holders of government-issued quotas in major  
peanut-producing states like Georgia and Alabama, the assessment 
would amount to about $6.10 for each ton of peanuts sold. 
</P>
<P>
	For growers of peanuts produced outside the quota system, mainly  
for export, the cost would run about $1.30 per ton. 
</P>
<P>
	If approved, farmers would begin paying the assessment for the  
first time on the 1999 crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan came last year from 20 farm groups in the nine major  
peanut-producing states. 
</P>
<P>
	But farmers from Georgia, Alabama and Florida have complained  
the final proposal approved by USDA would bar any of the money 
raised through the assessment from being used for production 
research. 
</P>
<P>
	The original plan submitted by growers allotted 20 percent for  
that purpose in hopes of finding ways to lower production costs and 
increase profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The research is vitally important in this,'' said Griggs, the  
Georgia farmer. ``They (USDA) knew how important those areas were 
to us and yet they chose to change it anyway. I'm extremely 
disappointed. Right now I'm not looking at it very favorably.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gamble believes the proposal will face trouble among farmers in  
Texas, Alabama and possibly Florida, while growers in Virginia and 
the Carolinas probably will support it. 
</P>
<P>
	A new National Peanut Board would administer the program under  
the Agriculture Department's direction. The program would be in 
addition to any state checkoffs already in place in the nine major 
peanut-producing states -- Georgia, Texas, Alabama, Florida, South 
Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, New Mexico, and Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	The board would have 20 peanut growers -- 10 members and 10  
alternates. Each member would represent a peanut-producing state, 
although the member's vote would be weighted by the value of 
production in that state. For instance, Georgia's vote would count 
as 38 percent because that state had that amount of the nation's 
peanut crop last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the nine big peanut states would have one board member.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Eds: Any eligible farmer who did not receive a ballot should  
call 888-720-9917. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
