<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs' Beck Has Arthroscopic Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Chicago Cubs closer Rod Beck underwent  
arthroscopic surgery on his right elbow Saturday and will be out 
from 6-12 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck, placed on the 15-day disabled list Monday, had two bone  
spurs and several chips removed during the operation by Dr. Warren 
King in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only time will tell how successful the surgery went,'' said  
Chicago general manager Ed Lynch, in Atlanta where the Cubs met the 
Braves on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six to 12 weeks is a lot of leeway. We're happy Rod feels  
better that the problem has been treated,'' Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Cubs acquired reliever Rick Aguilera from  
Minnesota. Aguilera, 37, was 3-1 with six saves in eight 
opportunities and a 1.27 ERA in 21 1-3 innings with the Twins. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch, however, said Beck 's situation had nothing to do with  
trading for Aguilera. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Aguilera decision had been in the works for some time,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs optioned left-handed reliever Ray King to Triple-A Iowa  
to make room for Aguilera. King made his major league debut Friday 
night against the Braves and gave up a run in two-thirds of an 
inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck had previously said surgery was inevitable but expressed  
hope he could postpone it until the offseason. He changed his mind 
Tuesday and sought out a second opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck is 2-4 with seven saves in 11 opportunities and a 10.54  
ERA. He was booed Sunday at Wrigley Field, when he retired just one 
of four Atlanta batters in an 8-5 loss. 
</P>
<P>
	The bone spur is an old injury that dates back to when Beck was  
with the San Francisco Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Cubs Manager Jim Riggleman has said the club knew about it when  
they signed him to a one-year, $4 million deal before last season. 
After Beck's 51 saves helped Chicago to the NL wild-card berth, he 
signed for two more years at $9.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck said he never considered having the problem corrected  
between seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't go see doctors just to see doctors,'' Beck said. ``You  
don't say when you've saved 30 games a year, `Let's go fix it.' If 
you're effective, you don't mess with it. But now I'm not 
effective.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:41:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freed POW Gets Heroes' Welcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- To the delight of cheering, flag-waving  
supporters, Army Spc. Steven Gonzales today cut down the last 
reminder that he had been held as a prisoner of war in Yugoslavia: 
the faded, weather-beaten yellow bow on a courthouse tree. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a large smile and his Army dress uniform, the  
22-year-old Gonzales hugged his parents, Rosie and Gilbert 
Gonzales, before handing the memento over to his mother, who had 
placed the ribbon on the tree nearly two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``A great relief,'' a grinning Gonzales declared as he took his  
seat of honor in the back of a 1963 Rolls-Royce convertible for a 
homecoming parade held Saturday in downtown Huntsville. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a far cry from his situation a month ago, when he was in  
captivity with two other U.S. soldiers for 32 days by Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,500 people lined Huntsville's streets, festooned in  
American and Texas flags to give Gonzales a hero's welcome home. 
</P>
<P>
	``My son was a marine, so he reminds me of him sometimes,'' Erma  
Stuart said. The 64-year-old traveled some 70 miles from the 
Houston area with her daughter to be a part of Gonzales' 
homecoming. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Taylor of Huntsville watched the parade with Charlotte  
Farkas of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here to welcome Steven Gonzales home and support his  
family, let him know that we love him and that we're happy that 
he's here,'' said Ms. Taylor, 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzales, a cavalry scout with the 1st Infantry Division, was  
captured March 31 on the Macedonian-Yugoslavian border with staff 
sergeants Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and 
Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic released them in early May after an appeal from the  
Rev. Jesse Jackson and other American clergy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
