<DOCNO> APW19990522.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 19:31:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Urges Greater Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVINGTON, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton on Saturday pressed the  
House for swift passage of gun-control legislation and prepared to 
propose that states be allowed to spend unemployment funds on paid 
leave for parents so they can spend more time with their new 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators mindful of April's fatal shootings at a Littleton,  
Colo., high school approved legislation last week that would 
require safety locks on new handguns, ban violent juveniles from 
purchasing a firearm, and stop the import of large ammunition 
clips. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the House of Representatives will pass every one of  
these commonsense efforts that the Senate has passed to protect our 
children from guns,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio address. 
``And I hope they'll do it before school lets out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary Panel  
said later Saturday that his panel will hold hearings on the Senate 
legislation on Thursday, but that no House vote is likely until 
after the Memorial Day recess. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the bill that the Senate passed is a good bill,'' Hyde  
said on CNN's ``Evans, Novak, Hunt &AMP; Shields.'' ``I don't have any 
real problems with it, but we ought to hold hearings. ... It won't 
be more than a couple of weeks and we'll past a bill that I think 
will be satisfactory and the president will sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, aides said Clinton planned to unveil on Sunday in  
Grambling, La., a new administration study showing that the 
increasing responsibilities of the workplace were cutting deeply 
into America's family time. In conjunction with release of the 
study, he was directing the Labor Department to formulate 
regulations that would allow states to legislate changes under 
which surplus unemployment funds -- which are operated by the states 
-- could be used for parental leave. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of a lot of changes in the last 30 years, people are  
working harder and are under a lot more stresses,'' said White 
House domestic policy adviser Bruce Reed. ``Government and business 
need to do anything they can to help parents spend more time with 
kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Clinton was responding to inquiries from Maryland,  
Massachusetts, Vermont and Washington State in issuing a directive 
that would allow the paid leave for new parents, including those 
who adopt. 
</P>
<P>
	The new study from the White House Council of Economic Advisers  
found that over the last 30 years, the quality time parents can 
spend with their children has decreased by 14 percent, Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton met privately with Senate Democrats at an Irvington inn  
Saturday afternoon to thank them for voting for the gun-control 
bill and to discuss strategy on Kosovo, Social Security, Medicare 
and the federal budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke for more than an hour, promising to present  
his plan to shore up the Medicare system next month and asking for 
help in shepherding his nominations to approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has sent 170 nominations to the Senate during the  
current Congress that began in January, White House spokesman Jake 
Siewert said, and only 34 have been confirmed. None of the 38 
nominees whose names he has submitted this year to be federal 
judges has received a hearing, Siewert said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the meeting, Clinton played a round of golf with a group  
of senators before returning to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the evening, Clinton told an Italian-American group  
that the key to reducing youth violence lies in the family and 
community. He said responsible parenting can counteract the 
thousands of violent images children see in the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at Sons of Italy Foundation's annual dinner, Clinton  
called on parents to lead by example and show the country's 
children the evils of prejudice. He asked the audience to provide 
``every decent person a home in America'' and cited NATO's mission 
against Yugoslavia as an example of living by such values. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important job of any society is not in the creation  
of wealth, but in the richness and wholeness in the lives of the 
children,'' Clinton said. ``There is no more important work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton visited  
Littleton's Columbine High School on Thursday, one month after two 
students killed 12 classmates and a teacher before committing 
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton visited with victims' families and other community  
members. 
</P>
<P>
	The morning of Clinton's departure for Colorado, a student in  
Conyers, Ga., opened fire at his high school, wounding several 
classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``No child should have to worry that a classmate is carrying a  
loaded gun to school. No parent should have to fear sending a child 
to school,'' Clinton said in his radio address. ``No American 
should tolerate this level of violence against our children. There 
is no task more urgent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton lauded House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., for his  
support for requiring background checks on sales at gun shows and 
raise the age for handgun ownership to 21. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said parents must pay ``attention to the shows their  
children watch, the Web pages they visit, refusing to buy products 
that glorify violence,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has challenged Hollywood to refrain from showing guns in  
movie ads and previews, strictly enforce its ratings system in 
theaters, and re-evaluate the content allowed in PG-rated films. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't forget the children of Columbine and all the other  
children who were lost because their culture, their society is too 
violent, their laws too lax,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 22:21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emmy-Winning TV Producer Dies at 78 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert Carr Doyle, an Emmy-winning television  
producer who helped launch ``The Huntley-Brinkley Report'' and the 
National Geographic Society's TV nature specials, is dead at age 
78. 
</P>
<P>
	He died Friday at Suburban Hospital of pneumonia.  
</P>
<P>
	Doyle won an Emmy Award for his work on the NBC-TV show that  
paired anchors David Brinkley in Washington and Chet Huntley in New 
York and later worked for the National Geographic from 1962 to 
1972, producing 28 nature documentary specials that won him other 
Emmy and Peabody awards. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked with such figures as Louis Leakey, Jane Goodall and  
Jacques Cousteau on the specials. 
</P>
<P>
	During his years with NBC from 1946 to 1953 he was involved with  
the first broadcasts of national political conventions and had 
coached four presidents, Harry S. Truman, Dwight D. Eisenhower, 
Lyndon Baines Johnson and Richard M. Nixon, on the use of 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been a consultant since leaving the National Geographic  
in 1972. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 07:31:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Greater Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is urging House Democrats to  
insist on passing gun restrictions beyond those approved by the 
Senate, administration and Democratic aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shouldn't settle'' for the Senate's limited restrictions,  
such as mandatory background checks for all firearms transactions 
at gun shows and pawn shops, Clinton told 18 House Democrats 
Friday, said the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the group the House should pass additional  
provisions that would raise from 18 to 21 the legal age for 
possessing and purchasing handguns, semiautomatic assault weapons 
and high-capacity ammunition clips. 
</P>
<P>
	The aides said Clinton delivered that message to the House  
Democrats during a private White House meeting to plot strategy in 
the gun control debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Publicly, Clinton is urging the House to pass the new  
restrictions approved by the Senate, including mandatory background 
checks on all firearms transactions at gun shows and pawn shops. 
</P>
<P>
	In his weekly radio address today, Clinton urged the House to  
``immediately'' approve the restrictions in the Senate bill and 
reject the House Republican plan to let the explosive debate cool 
off until next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``I call on the House to take immediate action,'' Clinton said.  
He pressed the House to approve ``every one'' of the Senate bill's 
new restrictions on gun control, which were propelled to passage 
Thursday in the wake of high school shootings in Colorado and 
Georgia. In his prepared remarks he made no mention of the 
provisions he discussed with the House Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't once again let the gears of politics as usual grind  
our urgency into dust,'' Clinton added. 
</P>
<P>
	As lawmakers headed home for the weekend, there was no consensus  
over which provisions to press for in the House. But hoping to 
benefit from the momentum of the Senate's juvenile justice bill, 
Democrats were united in pushing for House action on those issues 
by Memorial Day, at the end of this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Republicans refused to budge from their plans for  
Judiciary Committee hearings on the matter Thursday and floor 
debate in mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to make sure that we do this in a reasonable,  
rational and responsible way, and that requires us to go through 
the ... Judiciary Committee,'' said John Feehery, spokesman for 
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the families of the victims of the Columbine High  
School shooting in Colorado and those shot Thursday in Georgia 
deserve quicker action. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not take a Memorial Day recess until we pass a  
proper memorial for the slain students in Littleton, Colo., and 
other school gun tragedies,'' said Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, 
the Judiciary Committee's ranking Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	House Republicans were eager to let the issue cool off after it  
caused a public relations meltdown for their party during two 
volatile weeks of Senate debate. To that end, they were expected to 
change the subject in their weekly radio address from guns to 
proposals that would limit the ways in which Congress can spend 
Social Security funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Public sentiment and Democratic pressure in the wake of the  
Colorado shootings prompted Senate Republicans to retreat on gun 
policy several times before lawmakers included new firearms 
restrictions in the final bill that passed Thursday, 73-25. 
</P>
<P>
	Led by Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, a member of the board of the  
National Rifle Association, Republicans initially defeated a 
Democratic amendment that would require background checks on all 
firearms purchases at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	But after a half-dozen Republicans complained to Craig only a  
few hours later, Republicans agreed to make those checks mandatory. 
By the final vote, senators of both parties also approved 
provisions that would require background checks for all gun 
transactions at pawn shops and all handguns to be sold with trigger 
locks. 
</P>
<P>
	In an additional defeat, public pressure to pass a juvenile  
justice bill forced Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to 
back down on his threat to kill the bill outright. 
</P>
<P>
	In a stunning climax just hours after the shootings in suburban  
Atlanta, Vice President and White House hopeful Al Gore broke a 
tie, casting the deciding vote in favor of a Democratic amendment 
imposing still more restrictions on guns that the Senate had 
rejected a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, more Republicans voted for the underlying bill,  
sponsored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, than opposed it. Lott was 
among those who voted for it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990522.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 19:31:14 </DATE_TIME>
