<DOCNO> APW19990522.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 01:41:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Forecaster Looks Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- Although he has become famous as the  
nation's preeminent hurricane forecaster, Bill Gray thinks that 
will only be a footnote in his biography. 
</P>
<P>
	``My most important work is the graduate students I've had and  
turned out,'' said the Colorado State University researcher. ``A 
lot of them are leaders in the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Friday, former director of the National Weather Service,  
says Gray ``has made some of the most important contributions to 
the study of how tropical storms develop in varying climactic 
regimes. And he did it before those kinds of connections were 
understood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It all started with a wild ride through a hurricane 30 years ago  
at 1,500 feet in the nose bubble of an Air Force bomber. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Air Force officer and University of Chicago Ph.D.  
speaks plainly despite a slight stutter. There's nothing fancy 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	He likes classical music, country and western and drives a beat  
up 1979 Chevy Malibu. At age 69, the slender, 6-foot-5 scientist 
still runs in 10-K races at this mile-high altitude. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked to pinpoint the biggest prediction success he's had,  
Gray says, ``I'm surprised any of it worked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's been studying hurricanes for 40 years. From his perch in  
the foothills of the Rocky Mountains, he has produced an annual 
forecast that is eagerly awaited on the Atlantic Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	And not just by the public. The National Hurricane Center, the  
National Weather Service and local officials like Billy Wagner, 
emergency manager for the Florida Keys, give it considerable 
weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``He tries to target the potential of hurricanes hitting land,''  
the chief concern of officials and the growing number of people 
living along the Atlantic Coast, Wagner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray has been running his forecast operation, which is separate  
from his teaching at Colorado State, on a shoestring. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, he says, the funding may run out. The insurance  
agencies that formerly helped pay his costs now can get his 
predictions free online. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal agencies are rejecting requests for funding for Gray's  
hurricane forecasting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the best climate team anywhere dollar for dollar''  
before he had to begin cutting back. Still, he isn't likely to 
quit. ``It's just a question of how much of my house I'd 
mortgage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gray opts for forecasts based on statistics from observations of  
past weather. Numeric modeling projections from existing conditions 
dominates in the weather prediction business these days. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray argues too many forces are at work over oceans to project  
what will happen without looking at the past. He also has convinced 
skeptics that conditions elsewhere, including rainfall over West 
Africa, help determine how many hurricanes will develop each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray is credited with showing that El Nino, while wreaking havoc  
elsewhere, cut down on hurricanes along the Atlantic. He learned 
that painfully, after the phenomenon resulted in his 1997 forecast 
being the least accurate. 
</P>
<P>
	This year he is predicting 14 storms powerful enough to be named  
-- nine hurricanes, four of them major, with a 54 percent 
probability at least one will hit the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Gray is worried that the public has been lulled into a sense of  
complacency. 
</P>
<P>
	``The young people and retired people who moved to Florida in  
recent years don't understand the threat because there haven't been 
many major storms since 1960,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with thousands of new homes built along the coast, Gray  
says the region is entering a period of more intense storms. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we are going to see more hurricane damage than ever  
before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Gray says, ``I think people wanting to live along the  
coast is fine. They just must be willing to pay for it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
