<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russia Says NATO Undermining Peace  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia accused NATO today of undermining its  
efforts to find a peaceful settlement to the Kosovo conflict and 
said the alliance was trying to evade responsibility for bombing 
civilian targets. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov told CNN that as 
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin arrived in the Yugoslav capital, 
Belgrade, ``the intensity of the bombing reaches its peak.'' NATO 
forces mistakenly hit an ethnic Albanian rebel base, the alliance 
said today, the same day its jets and missiles knocked out power to 
much of Serbia and destroyed a residence of President Slobodan 
Milosevic. 

</P>
<P>
	China Unveils Embassy Attack Exhibit  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Anger flared anew in Beijing today as visitors  
toured an exhibition of photos chronicling NATO's May 7 attack on 
the Chinese Embassy and the damage wrought by the alliance's 
continuing air campaign against Yugoslavia. The exhibition at the 
National Art Museum adds to an anti-NATO, anti-U.S. government 
propaganda campaign. Images at the exhibition portrayed the Chinese 
and Yugoslav people as common victims of NATO aggression. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Greater Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	IRVINGTON, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton today pressed the House  
for swift passage of gun-control legislation, saying children 
should not have to worry that classmates might bring weapons to 
school. Senators mindful of April's fatal shootings at Columbine 
high school approved legislation last week that would require 
safety locks on new handguns and ban violent juveniles from 
purchasing a firearm. ``I hope the House of Representatives will 
pass every one of these commonsense efforts,'' Clinton said. ``And 
I hope they'll do it before school lets out.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NRA Says Gun Laws Won't Help  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- More gun laws won't prevent school shootings  
like the recent massacre at Columbine, and those who seek further 
restrictions ultimately want to take away people's right to bear 
arms, a National Rifle Association leader said today. ``In 
Littleton, those two horrible kids, homicidal maniacs, they broke 
20 federal and state gun laws,'' Wayne LaPierre, the group's 
executive vice president, told Georgia Republicans. Presidential 
candidate Steve Forbes urged Americans to fight school violence as 
they would a war. Speakers at the gathering charged repeatedly that 
the Clinton administration hasn't vigorously enforced existing gun 
laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Areas Gird for New Season  
</P>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Another six-month Atlantic hurricane  
season starts June 1, and some areas of the Florida Keys, Honduras, 
Haiti and the Dominican Republic hit by last year's monster storms 
are unprepared for another round that could be equally brutal. 
Forecasters say cyclical changes could signal an upswing not seen 
for 50 years. ``People have been saying for several years we may be 
heading back to a period like the '40s and '50s when we really had 
heavy hurricane seasons,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of the 
National Hurricane Center in Miami. ``I think we are in it now.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pisa Tower Leans Less After Fixing  
</P>
<P>
	PISA, Italy (AP) -- The Leaning Tower of Pisa is leaning a little  
less thanks to an experiment aimed at making the monument settle 
better into the ground, experts said today. In February, workers 
started removing soil from under the tower's base. Going into the 
experiment, the 12th century tower leaned some 6 degrees -- 13 feet 
-- off the perpendicular. Experts reported today that the tower has 
since straightened by about one-fifth of an inch. 

</P>
<P>
	Tigers 6, Indians 2  
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Rookie Jeff Weaver defeated Cleveland for the  
second time in a week today as the Detroit Tigers downed the 
Indians 6-2 in a game featuring a bench-clearing incident touched 
off by beanballs in the sixth inning. Indians outfielder Manny 
Ramirez was the only player ejected after Cleveland starter Jaret 
Wright (4-2) and Weaver (5-3) took turns hitting batters in the 
head with pitches in the sixth. 

</P>
<P>
	Capriati Wins First Title in 6 Years  
</P>
<P>
	STRASBOURG, France (AP) -- Jennifer Capriati won her first event  
in six years today when she defeated Russia's Elena Likhovtseva in 
the final of the Strasbourg Open. The 23-year-old American took 59 
minutes to down the second-seeded Likhovtseva 6-1, 6-3, completing 
a straight-sets sweep of the tournament. The victory was a 
dramatic, positive step in Capriati's comeback and boosted her 
prospects for next week's French Open. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
