<HEADLINE> Hartwig, Price-Smith Enjoy US Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- A rare chance to compete close to home  
brought out the best in pole vaulter Jeff Hartwig and shot putter 
Connie Price-Smith Saturday in the U.S. Open track and field meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``About half the people on this side of the stands are my family  
and friends,'' Hartwig said. ``I was excited just to come out and 
have a chance to jump for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig, ranked No. 2 in the world, won at 19 feet 1-4 inch, and  
Price-Smith, ranked No. 3, won by more than two feet at 62-8 1-2 -- 
the best in the world this year. Both are from nearby St. Charles, 
Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Price-Smith, 36, a three-time Olympian, actually had the best  
heave of her life at the end of warmups. Competing in the St. Louis 
area for the first time since the 1994 Olympic Festival, she had a 
65-foot effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Hartwig, 31, topped 19 feet for the second time outdoors this  
year despite a difficult cross wind. He didn't come close to three 
shots at 19-4 1-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it doesn't feel that strong, when you're holding a  
17-foot pole, that thing catches wind like a sailboat mast and it 
just blows around,'' Hartwig said. ``You're trying to control it 
while you're trying to run full-speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anna Jakubczack of Poland also set a world best this year in the  
1,500 mets, winning in 4:08.77. Larry Wade of HSI tied his own 
world best in the 110 high hurdles for the third time in 13.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheri Kenah of Reebok Enclave had the best American time this  
year in the 1,500, finishing second in 4:09.33. Jearl Miles-Clark 
won her outdoor debut in the women's 800 with a late kick. 
</P>
</TEXT>
