<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kids Finding Ways To Get Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From his grandfather's house, 12-year-old  
Andrew Golden got the guns he used to shoot up his Jonesboro, Ark., 
classmates. In Colorado, Dylan Klebold had his girlfriend buy guns 
for him because she was just old enough to make a legal purchase 
and he wasn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are typical of the ways youngsters in America fairly easily  
can put their hands on guns, according to some of the first 
research into the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want a gun, you're going to get a gun,'' says John  
Cummings, a 17-year-old high school junior from Sherman Station, 
Maine, a small town where hunting is common. 
</P>
<P>
	With more than 200 million guns estimated in circulation in the  
United States -- many in homes for hunting or protection -- it is 
hard to keep guns effectively locked away from or inaccessible to 
children, many experts believe. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-year-old accused of wounding six classmates Thursday in  
Conyers, Ga., got a rifle and .357 Magnum revolver by breaking into 
a locked cabinet in his family's basement, officials say. His 
stepfather kept guns for hunting. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has preoccupied many Americans since the Littleton,  
Colo., school shooting a month ago. It also has gotten lawmakers' 
attention as the House debates whether to tighten gun laws, 
including raising the minimum age to buy a handgun to 21 from 18 or 
requiring child-safety locks on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Many gun-rights groups, as well as Cummings, the Maine  
teen-ager, say it is youngsters' personalities and cultural 
influences, not access to guns, that determine whether they commit 
violence. Teaching children about gun safety is vital, they argue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because I have access to a gun, that doesn't mean I'm  
going to go out and kill somebody,'' said Cummings, who took a 
safety course before receiving a state hunting license. ``Anyone 
who does that, they've got to be messed up in the head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Only in the past few years have government researchers studied  
how young people illegally obtain guns. 
</P>
<P>
	A report released this winter by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco  
and Firearms found that contrary to long-held belief, only 35 
percent of the guns juveniles used in crimes were stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	One-third to one-half were bought from licensed dealers by  
someone acting as a ``straw'' intermediary, such as a girlfriend or 
an illegal gun trafficker, the ATF found. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Littleton case, authorities contend that is what  
happened. Three guns were bought legally by the 18-year-old 
girlfriend of Klebold, who was 17, then were given to him and 
friend Eric Harris. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth weapon was bought by a 22-year-old man, who now faces  
charges of providing a handgun to a minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado authorities say they are treating the girlfriend as a  
witness. Federal authorities refuse to comment on whether she could 
be prosecuted under federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun groups say such cases prove federal authorities do not do  
enough under existing law to crack down on illegal traffickers or 
prosecute children found illegally with guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation has a zero-tolerance policy against young people  
bringing guns to school, notes James Baker, chief lobbyist for the 
National Rifle Association. Yet the federal government over the 
past two years prosecuted just eight children for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno, responding to such complaints, said  
last week that juvenile crime more appropriately is handled at the 
local level. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun restrictions like the Brady Law background check on  
potential gun buyers are intended as preventative measures, rather 
than as prosecution tools, Justice Department spokesman Brian Steel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Accidents are another major worry. About 200 children are killed  
and more than 1,000 injured each year in gun accidents. The Senate 
last week approved a measure that would require gun safety devices 
sold with all handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Jonesboro school attack, victims' families sued gun  
makers and the young shooters' families. The lawsuit charged that 
the guns Andrew Golden and a friend took from Andrew's 
grandfather's house were not secured in a gun vault and were 
defective because they did not include safety locks. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet even some gun-control groups say safety devices are not a  
full solution. Many devices can be bypassed by a teen-ager with a 
little ingenuity, says Kristen Rand of the anti-gun Violence Policy 
Center. Also, some of the most popular are flimsy plastic, which 
even a child could crush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
