<DOCNO> APW19990522.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boat Qualifies on Indy Front Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Billy Boat finally had something to smile  
about. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indianapolis 500 pole-winner a year ago, Boat crashed three  
times in the past week, including once on Saturday as he warmed up 
for his first qualification attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Morning rain, a drop in temperature and high humidity produced  
slippery track conditions. Boat lost traction for just an instant, 
but that was enough to send his car spinning first to the left, 
then to the right and into the Turn 2 wall with heavy damage to the 
right side. 
</P>
<P>
	Car owner A.J. Foyt, watching from trackside, slammed a green  
signal flag to the ground in disgust, then ran back to the garage 
to get his crew started repairing Boat's Dallara-Aurora. 
</P>
<P>
	Four-and-a-half hours later, with the rebuilt car, a relieved  
Boat completed four laps at an average 223.469 mph, putting him on 
the outside of the front row, next to Arie Luyendyk and Greg Ray 
for the May 30 race. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a stupid incident,'' Boat said. ``You've got to look at  
yourself in the mirror and say, `What's going on?' They just said, 
`Don't worry about it.' I knew we had the race car, and I knew we 
had the setup, but it's been a long week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boat first crashed on May 16, the second day of practice,  
causing heavy damage to the left side and rear. The next day, he 
crashed again, this time damaging the right side. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a really tough week,'' he said. ``I don't think you  
can appreciate qualifying for this race until you go through 
something like this. There's nothing given to anybody here, and my 
boss told me that better than anybody. I really have to thank the 
whole A.J. Foyt crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never once did he say anything negative to me. He's been there  
for me. I'm very fortunate he believes in me,'' Boat said of his 
car owner, a four-time Indy winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Boat qualified on the pole last year at 223.503 mph and led the  
first 12 laps. He finished 23rd after a bad drive line knocked him 
out after 111 laps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
