<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Star Wars' Crowds Pack Theaters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- According to Yoda: ``Size matters not.''  
</P>
<P>
	Except, of course, at the box office, where the ancient, green  
sage might have expected a little more. 
</P>
<P>
	After a strong midweek opening, ticket sales for the ``Stars  
Wars'' prequel fell short of some predictions Friday with a take of 
$18.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still doing terrific business, no question about it,''  
said Paul Dergarabedian, an entertainment analyst with Exhibitor 
Relations Co. ``It's just that the first day was so high that 
anything coming after is going to seem low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sci-fi epic opened with $28.5 million Wednesday, and  
garnered $13.2 million Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts expected the first non-school night showing of ``Star  
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace'' to draw hordes of children 
and shatter box office records. 
</P>
<P>
	But rather than help the film, the hype may have hurt it.  
</P>
<P>
	Many people may have avoided the film Friday because they  
thought the shows would be sold out, Dergarabedian said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They turn on the television and see all the long lines and the  
people in costume, and parents and those who aren't really 
voracious fans decide to try seeing the film next week instead,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Phantom Menace'' was expected to rebound Saturday because  
fewer people have to work and many may realize there are plenty of 
available tickets at the film's 2,970 venues. Saturday figures and 
Sunday estimates were expected Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have predicted the film will gross $120 million to $140  
million by Monday, but 20th Century Fox distribution chief Tom 
Sherak said people are placing too many expectations on the 
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let the picture play now,'' Sherak said. ``People have written  
that it is disappointing ... It's a great number!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Around-the-clock showings of the movie Wednesday helped ``The  
Phantom Menace'' set a new one-day record for box office receipts, 
beating previous title holder ``Lost World: Jurassic Park'' whose 
one-day earnings totaled $26.1 million in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Box office comparisons are not adjusted for inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
