<HEADLINE> Newcastle Soccer Fans Confront Cops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWCASTLE, England (AP) -- Disappointed Newcastle soccer fans who  
had watched their team lose the FA Cup to Manchester United on pub 
televisions Saturday, gathered in the city center until they were 
dispersed by police. 
</P>
<P>
	Police reported several small fights but no serious incidents.  
There were ``one or two'' arrests for disorder and a few people 
suffered minor injuries, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing serious but it's bubbling a bit,'' said acting  
Sgt. Brian Maxwell of Northumbria Police. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 450 of the fans massed in a central marketplace of this  
northern city. Some smashed telephone booths and threw bottles. 
Police dog handlers and mounted officers joined a line of police 
who forced the chanting crowd back and made the fans disperse. 
</P>
<P>
	At London's Wembley Stadium it was a higher-spirited celebration  
for Manchester United fans, whose team completed its third League 
and Cup double of the 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said at halftime there had been 16 arrests, all for minor  
public order or breach of the peace matters. 
</P>
<P>
	In Manchester, thousands of joyful fans packed pubs and clubs to  
cheer on their hometown victors. Drivers hooted their car horns and 
fans poured on to the streets after the final whistle blew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
