<DOCNO> APW19990522.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Convicts Julie Hiatt Steele </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jurors voted 9-3 to convict Julie Hiatt Steele  
and prosecutor Kenneth Starr should ``seriously consider'' retrying 
the case, the jury foreman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Hawxhurst said the evidence that Ms. Steele lied in Starr's  
investigation of President Clinton was ``very persuasive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr has until Tuesday to decide whether to seek a retrial of  
Ms. Steele on charges of falsely undercutting Kathleen Willey's 
story of an unwanted sexual advance by Clinton. The first trial 
ended May 7 in a mistrial. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreman, speaking publicly for the first time, said in an  
interview the vote to convict Ms. Steele was the same on each of 
the three charges of obstruction and one count of lying to the FBI. 
His remarks were the first by a juror in which the jury vote was 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawxhurst also said that one of the jurors who voted for  
acquittal ``refused to keep an open mind. When jury deliberations 
began, he said there was no way he was going to change his mind,'' 
said Hawxhurst. ``I felt that there was real bias there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hawxhurst is a retired Naval officer who works for Vredenburg, a  
management consulting firm in Reston, Va. ``I'm a Republican and 
somewhat conservative, but I believe I fairly listened and 
considered the evidence and rendered a fair verdict,'' said 
Hawxhurst. 
</P>
<P>
	A juror who voted to acquit Ms. Steele, Thomas Brown, said he  
felt the prosecutors' chief witness, Mrs. Willey, had ``zero 
credibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've met liars before, but this is the first time I've met one  
with papers to prove it,'' said Brown, a career civil servant at 
the Treasury Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown pointed to testimony in this month's trial that after Mrs.  
Willey was granted immunity from prosecution by Starr's office, she 
was caught lying to prosecutors about a relationship she had with 
another man. Starr's investigators subsequently promised in writing 
a second time that Mrs. Willey wouldn't be prosecuted. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown also said Starr's case was ``petty and mean-spirited.  
</P>
<P>
	``After hearing most of the evidence, I got to thinking this was  
the government taking the Thursday afternoon bridge club to federal 
court,'' said Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawxhurst said that among the most compelling evidence in the  
case was a videotape of Ms. Steele's appearance on CNN's ``Larry 
King Live'' in which she described a lengthy call from Mrs. Willey 
on a cell phone. Records introduced at the trial show the call 
lasted for less than a minute. In her TV appearance, Ms. Steele 
said Mrs. Willey told her for the first time in that phone call of 
an unwanted sexual advance by the president and asked her friend to 
lie about it to Newsweek magazine. Ms. Steele said she reluctantly 
went along after some discussion. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no way they could have talked about something that  
important in that short a time,'' said Hawxhurst. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey testified that she confided the alleged sexual  
advance by Clinton to Ms. Steele hours after the encounter occurred 
in 1993, not in the 1997 phone call from Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawxhurst said three witnesses who testified that Ms. Steele  
told them she'd known for a long time about the sexual advance gave 
``extremely strong testimony. Two of the women didn't even want to 
be there testifying, yet I think they felt an obligation to tell 
the truth, even though it hurt their friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said what ``swayed me'' to vote for acquittal was that  
there were ``too many alternative ways'' all the witnesses and Ms. 
Steele could have learned of the alleged sexual advance by Clinton 
on Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The witnesses were acquaintances of both the defendant and her  
accuser, so it would be impossible to prove beyond a reasonable 
doubt who told them,'' said Brown. Three prosecution witnesses 
testified they were told that Ms. Steele knew prior to 1997 about 
the alleged encounter between Clinton and Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta Geck, a juror who voted to convict, said ``I thought''  
Mrs. Willey ``was a good witness'' and ``I thought she handled 
herself very well on the stand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Geck said she didn't find it implausible that Mrs. Willey  
was unable to recall many details of the alleged sexual advance in 
January 1998 during the Paula Jones case, while providing 
meticulous detail weeks later to Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey explained that she had been badgered by the  
president's lawyer and threatened by an unidentified jogger two 
days before she testified in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case 
against the president. Mrs. Willey also said she was too upset by 
her husband's disappearance to remember that she had confided the 
alleged incident with Clinton to Ms. Steele just hours after it 
occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, things were confusing, but heaven forbid that all of a  
sudden such things should happen to us,'' said Mrs. Geck. ``She was 
approached'' by Clinton ``and she was threatened. I'd be frightened 
for my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele did not testify at her trial.  
</P>
<P>
	``Some of us thought that she should have been on there  
testifying,'' Mrs. Geck said of Ms. Steele. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
